#BalloInSingapore Day 7
There are few hours in life more agreeable than the hour dedicated to the ceremony known as afternoon tea.
Emily had Mindy and Ballo has- Pinky Pinky Sharma who suggested we go for high tea similar to Duchess of Bedford  Anna (year 1840) who made the tradition of sipping tea and nibbling sandwiches in middle of afternoon fashionable .
But we are crazy (not so rich) Asians , we will enjoy the British tradition in Singapore . 
It was so much fun to meet women with pink hats all together to raise awareness about breast cancer by meeting and donating at high tea event .
When was the last time you went for high tea asks Ballo.

Revisited Punggol Waterway to Coney Island on bike couple of weeks back. Was a nice, chill way to spend a morning on a weekday, with only a couple of old uncles hanging out amongst the Casuarina groves on Coney Island. Varied terrain from well-paved paths to unpaved dirt. Avoided the beach areas because the last time I was there, the sandflies were vicious! Sad that I dropped the cam which now has scratched lens (hence what looks like a permanent water droplet in middle of video ğŸ˜©) Best were the yummy chicken wings at WingZone Punggol end of the ride. It was a bright day (sunburn liao) and I followed @photographyholic, @vincentphotogram and @ongwill to Kampung Lorong Buangkok - a neighborhood dearly loved by many Singaporeans as we wish we could have chicken running around in our backyard and a mango tree beside the house with the mango hanging outside the window.

Uncle Sng was very friendly and it was a good long chat with Saiful too, which shared the vantage point to shoot his house like a drone without a drone ğŸ˜¬

Believe it or not, it was my first time coming here, and I think next time I would sit for a kopi and pisang goreng. Anyone wants to join?

All pictures from #Pixel3 cos I brought #NikonZ6 with big fat lens and yet forgot to put the XQD card inside, and yes no one else shoots that that card. ğŸ˜…

PS. If you go there for some shots, please be respectful. The aunty at the yellow house is quite old and she needs her nap in the afternoon, please be quiet. Keep in mind you are in private property although there is no fence for some of the houses. This is not a zoo and these people are not a display for your camera. This is their home, their life. If you have a few minutes to say hi and chat, you will leave with a lot of stories like I did today.

Built in 1900, this colorful house used to be the house of Tan Teng Niah, a businessman that owned sweet-making factories! It is situated in Little India, an area that I have only explored a few times during school trips or as a â€œtour guideâ€ for my foreign friends!

What I truly miss about traveling is the freedom to roam the streets randomly and learning about the heritage and the way of life of the locals. While travel is still on hold, I am bringing this wanderlust to rediscover Singapore as I explore a different part of the country weekly, and I am not disappointed at all!

Anyone else wanna explore other parts of Singapore together?

An illustration of Victoria Theatre and concert hall, one of Singaporeâ€™s oldest performing art centre with its classic European architectural style.

I had made an effort to drop by one of the day to look at this historic landmark to gather details, perspective and depth of the building.

It has been a challenge for me as this illustration take me lots of focus. It has in another way help push my skill forward, enable me to have a deeper knowledge and understanding of art and illustration.

I am happy to share this illustration with @munping23 of @theartshouse. Thanks for the support you give.

This pretty shop selling Arabic-style lights looks like a typical shop in Turkey but it is actually located in Kampong Glam right here in Singapore!

Kampong Glam is an eclectic blend of history, culture and a trendy lifestyle scene. Traditional stores selling textile and handicrafts, such as the one seen here, exist happily alongside hipster cafes and designer labels.

I love old neighbourhood where you find old gem like this! Although it has been closed for many years but one can imagine how it was like in its heydays back in the 70s where itâ€™s considered as a high class barber and beauty salon!

This shop is like a time capsule where time stood still. Can you guess when they cease operation based on these photos?

#ShotOniPhone #iPhone11ProMax

Rojak Flower / Torch Ginger Flower / Bunga Kantan. Delighted to see it again. It used to grow in our garden and mom would simply add it to a dinner salad. Finely julienned, a whisper of it  adds a distinct floral note to our local hawker favourite Rojak. If the Rojak man didn't display it in his store window, Auntie F would refuse to order it. It's also used in Penang Assam Laksa, which if you're lucky enough to have the real thing, is one of the most umami loaded seafood briny noodle soup we know of.

There's a new premium salon on the block. Enso Hair Studio is the go-to salon in the heart of Singapore's CBD. They're aiming for the stars, carving a place in Singapore's hair industry underneath the towers of Raffles City. The hair artists are skilled at providing hair solutions such as hair styling, hair colouring, blowouts, hair texturing, as well as hair and scalp care. Need a proper perm? This artisan salon also provides root perms, fringe perms, and hair rebonding services. Heading out for the evening? Get an Evening Upstyle at this hair salon before you conquer the night.

<358> â€œTeleported Colonial Building!â€

At first glance, it looked as if a colonial house from more than a hundred years ago has been teleported to the present times!

The truth is this pair of Edwardian era (1901-1910) semi-detached houses known as Winsland House II at Penang Road (near Dhoby Ghaut)has existed since the  1910s. While its surroundings had completely transformed, it has stood the test of time.

William

GRATITUDE FROM THE HEART 
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Lloyd's Inn Singapore: To all guests (past, present, future), thank you for your support. We are proud to say that during the last few months, trying as they may be, we neither cut wages nor let go of staff. This is because of the support from the local staycation market. In fact, we are hiring additional members to the team. 
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Every booking made supports consumption in the domestic tourism industry. Every staycation supports the livelihood of our team. Although business is not as optimal as pre-Covid times, we endeavour to preserve the staycation spirit for as best as we can. 
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
In our in-room guide, we have curated local experiences one can enjoy and explore. On social media, we will continue sharing our own travel experiences within Singapore via #lloydsinnexplores. 
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
We do encourage all locals to visit the attractions and experiences around Singapore. With the $100 #SingapoRediscovers incentive given by the government, spending it either on Staycations or exploring new sights, it is a cause we support for the local tourism industry. A little spending from each person goes a long way in supporting someone else's livelihood.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
We champion for an inclusive nation with mutual support and hope to offer other tourism businesses support as well. Thank you all for your support, and see you really soon at Lloyd's Inn or around Singapore! More on stories today on our team behind-the-scenes >>>

This is 1/6 of a sticker collection made for Children's Day 2020 that features marine life found in and around Singapore. These were personally designed and professionally printed and cut on 5-6cm glossy sticker paper. I've still got limited quantities (<30 per design) on hand, so check out my online shop if you wish to buy a fish.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] - Traditional Popiah

Rediscovery is about walking and finding unique place. Â 

As I rediscovered Joo Chiat, I came across Kway Guan Huat Joo Chiat - a traditionalÂ  Popiah maker since 1938 I was intrigued by the skill of those making the traditional popiah skin from dough. Great to see Chinese Fujian food culture still active and alive for over 80 years. It is also interesting to note that it coexisted for so many years next to the Malay enclave ( Geylang Serai) - Another reminder of our unique racial harmonious culture of Singapore.Â

I submitted this entry of a photo I took in May 2018, shortly before these iconic and colorful Rochor Centre buildings were demolished, for #shapesofhome and titled this as â€œHome At The End Of A Rainbowâ€ because this is what I think people should aspire to find instead of that highly touted pot of gold. Also the cheery and colorful sight of these buildings, that mark the district area of Bugis, now long gone, are bound to evoke a sense of #nostalgia for those in the know. These buildings also set the tone for future HDB flats by creating a splashing impact and timeless appreciation for them.

Occupying 24,000 square metres, the â€œArts in the Parkâ€ is a sculpture garden specially-designed for the residents of Sengkang. Look out for the â€œWavesâ€ sculptures which reminds us of Sengkang past as a fishing village and harbour. Many colourful textured ball sculptures are also designed to allow park users to simply sit back and laze on them. Put Sengkang Sculpture Park on the top of your to-do list when you visit Sengkang.

Our featured dimsum pastries are a satisfying snack for any time of the day. Traditionally a Cantonese cuisine, it was said that the origin of the egg tart was inspired by the English custard tart and Portuguese egg tarts. And instead of featuring the usual steamed Char Siew Pau, weâ€™ve selected the â€˜bakedâ€™ version where juicy BBQ pork is wrapped in crispy and buttery pastry. 

Make a trip to the nearest coffee shop, and keep a lookout for these savoury yummies in the window display. Best paired with a steaming glass of fragrant Kopi-O-Gao! Shiok!

Do you know of any hawkers who sell such freshly-made pastries? Comment below to tell us where you get your delicious pastries. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya!

Chinatownâ 
â 
Long before the arrival of Raffles in 1819, a small immigrant Chinese population had already settled in Singapore, cultivating gambier and pepper. When Singaporeâ€™s free port was established, more Chinese and other immigrants flocked to its shores. For easy administration, Raffles grouped various immigrant communities into ethnic quarters. In his 4 November 1822 letter to the Town Committee the area from the â€œBoat Quay southwest bank of the Singapore Riverâ€ was designated a Chinese Kampong. This self-contained kampong or community settlement became the home of many Chinese immigrants, and a transit point for coolies (unskilled labourers) going to Malaya. That kampong and Chinese centre grew, eventually becoming Chinatown.â 
â 
The original kampong was divided into zones, a sector for each Chinese community of the same provincial origin and dialect group.â 
â 
Different trades were confined to specific areas, so each street took on its own identity. From delicacies to death-houses, there were businessmen, traders, craftsmen, hawkers and peddlers to provide all of the peoplesâ€™ needs. â 
â 
Chinatown has become Singaporeâ€™s largest Historic District. Its four sub-districts â€“ Bukit Pasoh, Kreta Ayer, Telok Ayer and Tanjong Pagar â€“ were given conservation status in the late 1980s. Much of the town has changed, but fortunately, remnants of its colourful past are still present and old traditions have endured. During festivals such as the Lunar New Year, and the Mid-autumn Festival, there are celebrations and festive shopping. Always dressed for the occasion, Chinatown would be colourful, lit up and abuzz with activity, attracting not just the Chinese but other locals as well as tourists.â 
â .â 
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sgâ

Mini Bath Tubs
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 Â°C (160 Â°F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

HDB Kim Tian Green
Kim Tian Road, Singapore

Little India is filled with vibrant colours that represent its rich culture and heritage. Besides Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple on Serangoon Road, one of the oldest temples in Singapore that was built in 1881, you can also explore Shree Lakshminarayan Temple, Singaporeâ€™s first dedicated place of worship for Northern Indian Hindus.
Â 
Some other buildings that caught my eye over the years are two historical churches â€“ Kampong Kapor Methodist Church and Church of the True Light. Not forgetting the Abdul Gafoor Mosque and the eclectic exterior of Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple. All these buildings add unexpectedly to the vibrant facade of Little India.
Â 
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your own pictures with #SingapoRediscovers.

The next time you feel anxious, ask yourself this: Does this deserve my energy? If it is a no, take a deep breath, disconnect, and come back IN FORCE!

And anyways, we can't really go on a physical vacation, so we went to Sentosa Island, formerly used as a British military base and then a Japanese prisoner-of-war camp in Singapore. Home of many theme parks, resorts, fun attractions and beach clubs, a stop here is a must whether you are a visitor or a local! #SingapoRediscovers

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

Scenes from Sago Street

Singaporeâ€™s Chinatown precinct has been one of my favorite places to photograph since moving to this country about 18 months ago. Itâ€™s a bustling area where new and old traditions blend together, and thereâ€™s always something interesting to point the camera at. Itâ€™s a place full of life, but starting around the 1920s, Chinatownâ€™s Sago Street and Sago Lane were also a place full of death.

In that time, the area was home to many lower class Chinese immigrants. Superstition dictated that it was bad luck to die within oneâ€™s own home, and proper funerals were costly. Out of that sad reality came a pragmatic solution: death houses. For a small fee, the sick and elderly could live out their remaining days on the second floor of a death house. The first floor was reserved for funeral services.

Due to the poor conditions in death houses, the practice was eventually banned in 1961. Nowadays, all traces of the death houses have vanished, and the area between Sago Street and Sago Lane is the site of the well-known Buddha Tooth Relic Temple.

Did you know that the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India?

This is the first time Iâ€™ve actually explored Little India and glad that Iâ€™ve taken some photos of this unique place as a souvenir. 

There was even a friendly man telling me where I should take my photos and led me to a flock of pigeons which Iâ€™ve failed to capture the scene nicely because I didnâ€™t have the right lens setup at that time.

I would say this is the most fruitful photography session Iâ€™ve done in Singapore. I am also glad to have my first shoot this year (though tired of clocking 12k steps in that few hours) as the pandemic has kept us at home for the most part of the year.

Lately, I've been going around the touristy/non-touristy places to take photos. This has made me to discover and learn quite a number of things along the way.

Most importantly, it forces me to think out of the box, and create new perspective of the common scenes in Singapore, so as to make my photos more interesting to look at (hopefully). 

The walks have also reminded me that Singapore is a very interesting country. Like our hawker centre where you can find food from all over the world, Singapore has places that resembles all over the world too. So no more excuses to tell myself that Singapore is a "boring" place for photography because it is definitely not one!

A tip for those who wants to try doing this. Imagine you are a visitor from overseas paying $1k on air ticket to visit Singapore. How would you have made the trip worth it?

The Japanese Cemetery was a place I really wanted to visit post circuit breaker, and Iâ€™m glad I did. Build not only to commemorate various renowned Japanese figures who made an impact on Singapore, the place offers a gorgeous space that many can revel in whilst paying respects to the fallen.  I even got chance to interact with the janitor, who says he cleans the cemetery without fail everyday. Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. Itâ€™s an opportunity to re-live our nationâ€™s history while tuning into modern narratives of â€œhiddenâ€ spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

This Mid-Autumn Festival, @gardensbythebay is offering a brand-new festival experience - with a mixture of both online and offline programmes.

Take a stroll through the gorgeous Apricot Grove or watch the Royal Family's Walk display, which was first displayed at the Seoul Lantern Festival last year.

Another highlight of the festival is the Colonnade of Lights display which showcases 1,500 paper lanterns thoughtfully painted by the community and Gardens by the Bay's senior workers.

Besides these displays, they also offer hands-on activities such as learning how to make a snowskin mooncake or a DIY Good-Luck knot. If you're unable to make it down, you can still participate through the virtual space where exciting performances await you!

The festival and virtual programmes will be launched on 18 Sep and lasts till 4 Oct so mark your calendars now!

Entry is free so share this post with your friends and jio them for a Mid-Autumn outing!

ğŸ¡The Residence of Tan Teng Niah
.
A brightly colored landmark that stands along the arts belt in Little India. It is the last remaining Chinese villa in the history of Little India, Singapore.
Tan Teng Niah, a successful businessman who owned a confectionary business and various other smaller businesses, built the villa in 1900 for his wife. The Residence of Tan Teng Niah won the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention Award in 1991.
Was it always this colourful? The Residence of Tan Teng Niah villa was originally whitewashed. The colors were added fairly recently.
Found along Kerbau Road, it is probably one of the most photographed buildings in Little India.
.

Today, I didnâ€™t feel like I was getting â€œthe shot.â€ When I am in that mental state, I start blaming the weather conditions, locations, lack of interesting subjects, etc. And everything I shoot start to look like they are bad. But @sixstreetunder said in his Skillshare class that you have to know that â€œthe momentâ€ may not come that day. Maybe something that you expected may not happen. You need to always adjust yourself to the changing moment. Itâ€™s what street photography is about. 
So, I decided to read an art book of Monetâ€™s paintings to broaden my perspective. It said â€œDonâ€™t see objects before you such as houses, clouds, statues, as what they are but see them as geometric shapes with colors.â€ The perspective made sense when I went outside. I was just thinking too much about the subjects. Iâ€™ll let go of the stress and just try to enjoy the moment.
.

â€œOne thing I really love about Little India is its rich culture and history that also live within unassuming hotel buildings.
 
Many of the smaller hotels in Little India such as The Daulat and Perak Hotel started off as shophouses, and whatâ€™s not known to many is that Hotel 81 Rochor was first built just before the Second World War. The Great Madras also takes up a building that has been proudly perched on Madras Street since the 1940s.â€

<341> â€œRunning From A Hill To Anotherâ€

Can you imagine running from a hill to another via a bridge? 

As a young boy who grew up in Telok Blangah, I always had to chose between Mount Faber or Telok Blangah Hill for hiking. Itâ€™s too much a hassle to go up and down two hills at one go. 

The two neighbouring hills, which were then separated by a road, is now connected by a stylish wave-shaped bridge. The bridgeâ€™s shape creates shell-like sheltered spaces where visitors can rest and enjoy the scenery. But these resting areas have been closed by the authorities to avoid gathering of crowds.

Since there is no place to take a breather, I ran across the beautiful bridge as fast as I could like the man in front of me! 

William

Fort Gate, entrance to the British fort completed in 1860. Fort Canning was named after then-Governor-General of India, Lord Charles John Canning. It was built to protect Singapore from seaborne attacks. Fort Gate, the main entrance, faced the beach. A second purpose of the Fort was to be a refuge for the European population in the event of local unrest. #rediscoversg #singaporediscovers #whatmakessg #mysingapore

Chanced upon this row Peranakan shophouses just next to the bustling East Coast Road. This area - Joo Chiat/Katong - is fast becoming my favourite place to explore. Having been here thrice in the last month, especially when I live at the other end of Singapore, should be a testament to Joo Chiat/Katongâ€™s allure.

Aside from photographing these well-preserved Peranakan houses, this area has a plethora of good food! Thereâ€™s famous shops selling almost every dish thatâ€™s representative of Singapore, with my favourite being â€œDelicious Boneless Chicken Riceâ€ at Katong Shopping Centre.

While itâ€™s debatable whether chicken rice is a national dish, thereâ€™s definitely no debate that eating is our national past time. Couple that with a stroll within this historic precinct will make anyoneâ€™s experience a truly local one!

While I love bright bold colours that daytime photography can give me, it's quite tough to catch much sunlight after office hours.  So instead, I'm learning to embrace and enjoy night photography. post_caption:
<361> â€œDo you know where to look for eagles?â€

Do you know there is a place to watch eagles ğŸ¦… flying in the skies? 

I was searching high up for eagles through an circular structure situated at the end of the boardwalk. The blue sky was unbelievably beautiful filled with thin layers of clouds, but there was no sight of any eagle.

Surely there must be eagles in this place known as the Eagle Point at Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve. So I set my sights further and lower.  There, an eagle was swooping down close to the sea as if it was hunting for fish.  But it was too far for my phone camera to capture a close-up. Perhaps, I should really get myself a better camera one day. 

Still, I was delighted to catch a glimpse of an eagle!

William

ã€SengkangÂ #3 - Herbal Soupã€‘
Well known for its calmness and tranquility, Sengkang Riverside Park offers an array of activities for nature lovers. Designed with a â€œfruityâ€ theme, this wetland is about the size of a football field which helps to collect rainwater naturally through its aquatic plants. Wow!

As health foods go, herbal soup has been always been the favourite among many Singaporeans. Fragrant rice is cooked and served with a flavourful herbal chicken soup, believed to have benefits from detoxification to healing and strengthening the body. Each restaurant boasts its own closely-guarded secret herbal recipe of up to 20 different ingredients.

Make a trip to the nearest coffee shop and let us know where you get your healthy nutritious broth. A perfect pairing will be a glass of warm barley water! Burp!

Do you know of any hawkers that sell such herbal soup? Comment below to tell us where to find these delicious pastries. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.

Created an illustration of the famous Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, a historical temple located in the district of Chinatown. The architecture of the temple is inspired by Buddhist temples during the Tang Dynasty.

Rebecca pays a visit to the temple wearing a Mulan inspired red outfit. I wanted to inject a sense of liveliness in her clothes by painting it bold red.

She wanted to know more about Chinese culture and hope that through Singapore rediscovering temple trips, it will enable her to gain more insights about Buddhism history and culture.

A timely reminder to all in this COVID-19 Pandemic; Singapore's Ok! sculpture Park was built after Singapore successfully won the SARS outbreak in 2003. 

Each finger represent a message:
1) Eat healthy, exercise regularly 
2) Wash hand with soap frequently
3) Do not litter. Bag your rubbish and place in bin
4) See doctor, avoid crowded places if unwell. Spit, cough and sneeze into tissue
5) Keep public toilet clean. Keep places clean and free of pests.

This is an amazing place. Very huge natural setting. The data coverage is not great. Relive only captured 22min walkğŸ˜…
Very glad to have spent time talking to Mr David Li who is an NParks volunteer here at this one of 4 awesome nature parks in Singapore. Learnt alot.

Do note that there are CROCODILES here. Near enough to get you worried (see video). The authorities (with expert assessment) have repeatedly declared that it is totally safe. Crocodiles here have enough to eat in the mangrove water eg fish (no need to go down and let them have more), and also crocs by nature actually shy away from people (see video). Reports of regular croc attacks around the world may not be applicable here at this reserve.

BUT - like the many monkeys and wild boars everywhere, you stay AWAY from them. Do NOT go near their territory. If they do ever come UP to cross the roads, they are just sharing space with us. Slowly move away from them. Do not go near to take Insta worthy shots. It might go viral ğŸ˜…

So yes it's safe but know that you're in a nature reserve. Respect their space. Do volunteer too, to help NParkâ¤ï¸ Give back to nature, and be rewarded with joy. 

Bring your loved ones. Or take a lovely stroll yourselves. I was gonna say, sit by the waters and read a book but hmmm maybe not here ğŸ˜Š

Have fun!!!

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

At City Vue @ Henderson, you will discover plenty of recreational options that cater to the residents of all ages. Children will enjoy playing at the childrenâ€™s playgrounds. Fitness enthusiasts can stretch their muscles at the adult and elderly fitness stations, or engage in games at the hard courts. Those who wish to gather with the neighbours for a friendly chat can do so at the resting shelters and precinct pavilions. The roof garden above the multi-storey carpark will provide an ideal spot for quiet contemplation or an evening stroll.

Located at the junction of Tiong Bahru Road and Henderson Road, City Vue @ Henderson is sited close to Tiong Bahru MRT station and Tiong Bahru Plaza.

This development comprises 5 residential blocks ranging from 27, 40 and 48 storeys public housing flats. There are total of 1,232 units of 2-, 3-, 4- and 5-room Standard Flats.

The name City-Vue @ Henderson reflects its prime location close to the city.

Rediscovering Singapore is as simple as taking a walk armed with a camera. Here in Little India, beyond the dazzling Deepavali lights, the simplest scenes were my richest discoveries.

After my shave, I chanced upon The Heritage shop. Home to a variety of antiques, I was really surprised they even carried the Canon 518 Super 8 movie camera (google it, itâ€™s vintage!). Step inside and youâ€™ll be transported to 40 years ago, which was when owner Mr Patrick started amassing his collection. He respectfully declined a photograph of the shopâ€™s interior as he charges for it. However, he welcomes all to visit his place. 

Crawford street was my final stop. Allegedly home to some of Singaporeâ€™s oldest shops, what drew my eye was Adiâ€™s barber. What sets this barber apart is itâ€™s high ceiling and television area. Owner Mr Adi left the shop untended for a bit, and then I realised how the residents really trusted one another enough to leave a shop open like Mr Adi. Beyond the long-established brick and mortar stalls, I sensed something that cannot be captured through photography alone - â€œkampung spiritâ€, that sense of community and resilience that transcends time and continues to live on in these hidden spaces. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. Itâ€™s an opportunity to re-live our nationâ€™s history while tuning into modern narratives of â€œhiddenâ€ spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

ã€Ang Mo Kio #4 - Ngoh Hiangã€‘
People living in Ang Mo Kio are pampered with plethora of hawker food spread over nine major hawker centers and many other coffee shops. If you have only a day to try all the different types of hawker food in Singapore, Ang Mo Kio is definitely the place to go.

The name â€™Ngoh Hiangâ€™ refers a fried meat roll filled with minced pork and prawn filling. This traditional dish is said to have originated in Fujian province in China and is named after the five-spice powder used in Chinese pork sausages.

Nowadays, we refer to Ngoh Hiang as a hawker stall selling a whole array of crispy deep-fried items, usually eaten with vermicelli for breakfast or a lunchtime treat. Century eggs, prawn crackers, fish cakes, â€˜guan changâ€™ (pink-coloured sausages) and of course Ngoh Hiang are some of the popular signature items. A Ngoh Hiang meal would not be complete without the accompanying bowls of pink, gooey sweet sauce and brownish savoury chilli sauce. It is not easy to find authentic versions of this well-loved meal these days, and hawkers continue to create more innovative items to vie for more regular fans. 

What are the items you like to include in your Ngoh Hiang meal? Comment below and share with us. See you on Thursday and see where we dabao this meal from, and where you can find a wide choices of ingredients. See ya!

The "Tropical Skyscraper", with the use of solar shading, communal gardens and external balconies. The tower is octogonal in plan, as the number "8" is associated with prosperity in Chinese culture.

The Baobabs, Flower Dome
5 October - 1 November

Make your way into an urban oasis and take respite amidst the luscious shades of green and sweet floral scents.

The sight of the brilliantly coloured macaws instantly captures our attention, as do the beautiful blooms of the bamboo orchid, a native species that is used extensively in the landscapes of our metropolitan city-state. Man is innately attracted to nature and seeks to make connections with other life forms. This affinity with the natural world is known as â€œbiophiliaâ€, meaning â€œa love of lifeâ€ in Greek.

The transformation from a Garden City to City in a Garden and the movement towards City in Nature have seen the integration of biophilic design into our concrete jungle. Treelined streets, skyrise greenery and world-class gardens and parks that teem with a diversity of flora and fauna are a reflection of how Singapore has successfully incorporated nature and its ecosystem into the urban fabric, integrating both harmoniously. These efforts have not only increased biodiversity in the city, but also influenced the way we work and play.

Redesign your work and living spaces by simply introducing some plants! Beyond their aesthetic value, plants also create a restorative environment to engage our senses, promote emotional and mental well-being, and boost productivity. Jam-packed with design and therapeutic benefits, it is no surprise that many have been drawn to nurture their green fingers whilst working from home! If youâ€™re new to introducing nature to your home or workspace, a good starter option would be the air plant, a low maintenance houseplant that can be used as a table centrepiece or hanging ornament. Alternatively, the use of cut flowers like the exotic birds of paradise seen on display can liven up your space effortlessly!

"All colours ğŸŒˆ on a tree!" 

Eucalyptus deglupta is a species of tall tree, commonly known as the rainbow eucalyptus, Mindanao gum, or rainbow gum that is native to the Philippines, Indonesia, and Papua New Guinea.
The rainbow effect is created as the bark peels off throughout each season, revealing the fresh, bright-green bark below.Â As each layer of bark matures, it turns shades of blue, purple, orange, and red.

If you want to know exactly how the trees' bark becomes rainbow-hued, or to witness this beautiful rainbow eucalyptus trees, you are in luck. 

Here in Singapore, the one and only! 
The heritage Mindanao Gum Tree in Katong Park, Singapore.

The third #SingapoRediscovers series: Changi Jurassic Mile. This newest and largest permanent outdoor display of life-sized dinosaurs is part of the Changi Airport connector and the opening was recently officiated by the Minister of Transport on 11 Oct 2020.

With this connector, we now have the option to cycle, walk and jog to East Coast Park and Marina Bay from Changi Airport (in addition to other modes of transport like the bus, train or taxi).

While admission is free, do remember to refer to the website to verify if you are required to do any pre-booking prior to your visit. As the path is also shared among cyclists, runners and pedestrians, let us remain vigilant and be considerate to ensure that all users are safe when visiting this attraction!

And yes, keep your hands and bodies off the exhibits please.

Another photo stop along Coney Island Promenade. 

There were many other families sitting around and enjoying the view. The Promenade is good for families with strollers as beyond that, the paths are not as smooth. 

There were also some picnic-goers, but if you intend to bring food, do be warned that there are monkeys in Coney Island. As we walked on, we saw a group of them picking up plastic bottles and food packets left behind by other visitors. A reminder to all to do our part to maintain the natural state of the island and letâ€™s not leave any rubbish behind.

"Kampong life"
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singaporeâ€™s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each otherâ€™s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkokâ€™s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

Let's talk about story-telling...

... through our tastebuds. The food we eat reveals where weâ€™ve lived or travelled, what we appreciate or feel inspired by, and who weâ€™ve met or spent time with. It is over a meal that we often share stories and create our own. As food brings people together, it becomes a story in itself.

In the first installation of our Culinary Series, we've handpicked impeccable restaurants for you to dine and delight in for your next staycay with us. With the exclusive dining discounts and complimentary hotel credits you get on our bookings, you can savour and save on the finest gastronomical creations by world-renowned chefs. ğŸ¤¤

Where better to immerse in a kaleidoscope of cultures - Chinatown, a place that draws generations of visitors to its peculiar charm. Just like itâ€™s contemporary counterparts, you can find relics that come alive in different forms by day and by night. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. Itâ€™s an opportunity to re-live our nationâ€™s history while tuning into modern narratives of â€œhiddenâ€ spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

There's a little fruit shop inside Tekka Market and it belongs to our friend Annie. The market which they are located in has quite a storied past. Tekka means "bamboo clumps" in Mandarin and was named after the bamboo that grew on either side of the canal. It was frequented by people from the working class, hence it became known as the "people's market". 

The original market across the road was demolished in 1982. Most of the store-holders, including Annie and family, relocated to the Tekka market that we know today. 

Our support for local businesses also mean this is the time when we will stop by and have some tropical fruits. We introduce you to fruits that are in season so you can have them at their absolute best (don't worry, durians not included ğŸ˜‚). This family business was started by her grandparents and has been in operations for more than 40 years, so its safe to say they know their stuff.

Yes, you heard me right, the least authentic Middle Eastern restaurant, Artichoke, led by the creative genius Chef Bjorn Shen, is still constantly revolutionizing the food and beverage scene based on strong beliefs and faith, without caring less of the norm.

The definite and right way of a proper dining experience at Artichoke is to start off with a bag of Turkish bread and a spread of mezzes. Mezzes are essentially a collection of small plates of food served as sharing appetizers to whet your appetite for the mains. What we have on the table are some of the mezzes that are new on the menu such as the Turkish Eggplant ($12), Sea Asparagus ($12) and Crab Toast ($16) while the Hummus with Iraqi Spiced Mushrooms ($14) is an improved version of the previous. The newly band of brothers are perfect to go alongside the Turkish bread, especially the hummus which is creamy, rich and just pure decadent; when paired with the abalone mushrooms that has been seasoned in Baharat, a thyme spice mixed of 7 spices, sauteÌed with olive oil and garlic. The more interesting dish is the Crab Toast whereby instead of a usual one-biter food, this is Artichokeâ€™s version of a two-biter open-faced â€œsandwichâ€, made with blue swimmer crab thatâ€™s mixed with Greek yogurt and other ingredients before topped on housebaked brioche. The finishing touches of adding deep-fried chicken skin and ikura creates the differing texture and flavour.
_________________
Artichoke Singapore
Address: 161, Middle Road, Singapore 188978

Did you know that the lush lawn in front of the Fort Canning Centre used to be a Christian cemetery? One can hardly tell when there. Despite the headstones on the side, there is a calm serenity on the lawn as people lay out their mats for picnics and kids run around playing catch. 

"Developed in 1822 by George Coleman â€“ Singaporeâ€™s first architect and Stamford Rafflesâ€™ consultant on the first Town Plan â€“ the Fort Canning Christian cemetery had approximately 600 graves interred.Â 

The cemetery was eventually closed in 1865, and the state of the burial grounds began to deteriorate. In 1953, the City Council exhumed the cemetery and created a â€œGarden of Memoryâ€."

Some of the headstones have been incorporated into a beautiful brickÂ wall that runs down the sloping hill.

The Development:

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

post_caption:
So the hermits finally decided to head out and visit the Cloud Forest at Gardens by the Bay over the weekend ğŸ˜‹. We had visited the Cloud Forest when Big E was still a pre-schooler and I remember she was rather scared of the height and loud noise from the waterfall, and it also felt too cold for us then as we weren't dressed for it ğŸ˜…. But this time round with the girls older and everyone dressed for it, the girls were able to better appreciate the environment and blooms. The mist, greens and light filtering in from the dome give the Cloud Forest such a magical quality that we all enjoyed the trip so much. 
.
If you're planning to visit too, do book your tickets early. We waited till the end of the week and by then most of the weekend slots were fully booked. But thanks to the limited capacity too, it wasn't crowded at all and we felt quite comfortable during our visit.
.
Btw you don't see many pics of us here, maybe it's just me but somehow with the masked faces, I find that the pics with us don't look so nice ğŸ˜… Anyway, we were all happy to be out finally and are now thinking of where to go for the coming weekend so we can book ahead if necessary ğŸ˜† Any suggestions? Meanwhile have a happy week ahead! ğŸ˜˜
.

Dealing with green is quite challenging.
Sometimes green in nature is overly vibrant. I sometimes reduce its intensity by lowering the saturation or by increasing its brightness. I could also shift its hue slightly to either yellow or aqua. Or I can reduce the contrast of the entire image so you can reduce the overall â€œpowerâ€ of the image. In any ways, the decisions are hugely influenced by the existence of the green. This time I tried to weaken the presence of the green by strengthen the power of red to counter (opposite color hue). I achieved the aged old photo look accidentally. Very interesting experiment.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Stepped out of the world of colour for a moment with a #SingapoRediscovers stay at @hotelmonosg this week.

As borders are set to remain close for some time, I decided to have a staycation in the heart of Chinatown. Little did I expect to find one that is so instagramable. Tucked along Mosque Street, @hotelmonosg is a chic hideaway set in six conserved shophouses of modern design. Glad to have stayed here as it gave me endless opportunities to discover all the history and culture within Chinatownâ€™s narrow alleyways. 

Hope that more Singapore residents will consider a local vacation so that we can all get to understand our culture, heritage better, and build a stronger Singapore identity together. @sgig @stb_sg #SGIGRediscovers

Festive Colours

Campbell Lane, situated just a street (Serangoon Road) from the ever popular Tekka Market, is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike. From my various visits (actually only twice in the last 2 weeks), it's always crowded and this is despite COVID still being a prevalent problem here in Singapore today. Its prime location between the Indian Heritage Centre and the Little India Arcade makes it a popular shopping street.

Walking along Campbell Lane, one may find themselves amongst garlands and other items that one may need for the Hindu festive season. Despite COVID-19, the festive mood is still present in Little India and many Hindu devotees still walk the streets of Little India looking for festive goods.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practiseÂ qigongÂ before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampungÂ spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

Very honoured to be part of @NeverBeforeSG; Singapore's first and largest online art showcase  presented by National Museum of Singapore @natmuseum_sg and curated by Yang Derong @derongisyang. 

Arranged in nine chapters about our take on #Covid19, it showcases 140 works by 91 Singapore based creatives who consist of photographers, videographers, writers, artists, architects and designers.

These are the images I captured during and after the â€œCircuit Breakerâ€. Most of the photos are primarily blue in colour, reflecting the blue mood: lots of uncertainty and a feeling of loneliness.

Blue, however, is also the colour of the sea and sky, which I was able to spend more time admiring and learning to appreciate nature more.

#NeverBeforeSG

Someday we'll look back and say that "Yes, those were crazy times. And we made it."

Someday.

post_caption:
Yesterday. All was peaceful and calm in the beautiful Bambusetum. The sun shone through the wispy bamboo leaves, casting dappled patterns on the path, and a slight breeze made them rustle soothingly. And then suddenly, the silence was broken. Someone was belting out Mandarin songs at the top of his voice. It seemed to be coming from the small gazebo perched above me. But as he was so enjoying himself and putting so much soulful expression into his songs, it seemed only right to leave him to it. He sure did have a powerful set of lungs though for he continued at full strength for more than an hour as I moseyed about the Learning Forest...

We are staying home this weekend, but here's a throwback to our @sentosa_island visit last weekend where we bought tonnes of goodies from @candyliciousshop! 
.
If you don't already know, there's a storewide sale at Candylicious now (swipe to see some of the stuff on sale!) and we went crazy loading up on discounted chocolates and candies. Regular items are discounted at 25% but some are sold at substantial discounts (up to 70% off) as they're close to expiry dates like end-October. My family are chocoholics, so we got some of the heavily discounted chocolates and within a week our purchases were already half gone ğŸ˜… We've always liked the variety of chocolates and candies at Candylicious, and they sure bring in a lot of interesting and good quality stuff.
.
The gelato counter is also having a 1-for-1 promo for their medium and large cups, so the kids finally got to eat their fav Blue Sky gelato! The Annette ice-creams are also going at 2 for $5! 
.
There was a short queue to enter the store the late afternoon Saturday we were there but the shop itself wasn't too crowded at all. Not sure how long the sale will last but if you want to go, Candylicious is now only open 2-9pm Thursdays-Sundays. 
.
We had such a fun time shopping and eating, hubs says we'll need to make another trip there to get more bargains ğŸ˜† How's your weekend going? ğŸ˜‰

I've passed by Bedok Reservoir Park numerous times on practically all sides, but this is the first time I've gone in! ğŸ˜…

It's a lovely place to exercise and de-stress, and quiet on a weekday early afternoon when I was there. One could sit with a book at the many sheltered spots in the park.

The solar farm is a great idea, making use of what nature provides. There's construction work going on, so I expect there'll be more attractions like the flying fox adventure parkÂ and kayaking coming up. I hope it won't get too busy, but I suppose Singapore has to optimise all its limited resources.

[Sembawang Precinct] Rediscover Sembawang hot spring with super grandma

Rediscovery is about going to a known place with a local "expert" and then appreciate the way of enjoyment of the place

Always go with an local â€œexpertâ€ when doing exploration. Come explore with super grandma Mdm Tan  to the only hotspring in Singapore. Just bring the essentials all in a plastic bag like a true blue Singapore veteran . She brought a pail, a scoop and a towel. That is all you need to enjoy the hot spring. 

If you want some better protection, you can bring an umbrella. For a complete experience, you can also bring some eggs to do hard boiled eggs with the hotspring water. 

This is the next best alternative to travelling for hotspring.

P.s. Mdm Tan is also featured in DBS  #protraitsofpurpose. Do support and vote for photo1 :) link in my profile.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Beyond the colorful

Rediscovery is about having a listening ear and appreciation to the heritage of the place.

Joo Chiat is a place with so much rich history as well as street â€œhistoriansâ€. In both visits, I have had strangers who are residents or former residents coming to chit chat with me. They told me interesting stories as well as places to shoot. Most of us, including myself, will focus a lot of attention on the colorful peranakan house.Â  One of them ( her name is Diana)Â  was told that there are more. For example, I should also be paying attention to the tiles of those other chinese or penakan houses. Those are imported from Europe in the pre-war days, and often use a symbol of wealth for people staying in the area.Â 

She also shared something interesting about what is shown in the last photo. Can you guess what that is for?

Kampong Glam is one of my go-to hangout spots but todayâ€™s visit was made even more meaningful through the #SingapoRediscovers campaign. At one of Singaporeâ€™s surviving street side barber, I waited in queue to get a shave. Mr Chen, unperturbed by onlookers, continued executing his craft like a hyper focused surgeon even as I hastily took a few snapshots. 
When it was my turn, Mr Chen introduced himself and swiftly finished the shave. We did not get to talk much though, as Mr Chen bantered with his friend who arrived shortly during my shave. In that moment, it felt like I returned to the 1990â€™s. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. Itâ€™s an opportunity to re-live our nationâ€™s history while tuning into modern narratives of â€œhiddenâ€ spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

post_caption:
<332> â€œA Fishing Platform Inside A Park!â€

Look at all those wooden planks, massive nets and house-like structure above the water! This place exudes the rustic charm of â€œkelongâ€, a Malay word that describes an offshore platform built by fishermen for fishing, which are commonly found in the coastal areas surrounding neighbouring countries such as Malaysia, the Philippines and Indonesia. 

I heard that a handful of â€œkelongâ€ remain around Singapore, but they are supposed to be out there somewhere in the seas. Yet, I discovered one right inside a park in a residential estate! 

William

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Today is the last day to join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest in collaboration with Singapore Tourism Board!

All you have to do is to check out our itinerary (link in bio), visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. Weâ€™ve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well! These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts.

3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3, Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers.

You will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th prizes: 4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket)
8th, 9th and 10th prizes: 3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

For more info on the contest and its T&Cs, please click on the link in bio.

Joo Chiat & Katong are places in Singapore that are rich in culture & heritage! Apart from the well-known Peranakan shophouses with their colourful motifs and famous food havens like Katong Laksa, you will find many hidden gems like the Former Queen's Theatre.

Besides Joo Chiat & Katong, we hope you had a great time rediscovering other places in Singapore. If you havenâ€™t, do join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest! All you have to do is to visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured in the itinerary and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. Click on the link in our bio to check out the itinerary!
 
3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3. Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers and a gentle reminder to make your account public so we are able to track your submissions!

Your submissions do not necessarily have to showcase the interior of the featured locations - any "hidden spots" within the precincts are welcome (the listed locations in the itinerary are just examples) A gentle reminder to exercise judgment and practise discretion when capturing these images too!

Winners will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket) and
3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

More info on the contest and its T&Cs can also be found on our link in bio.

Contest ends 4 October 2020, 2359 hours (GMT+08:00).

Did you know that this building is owned by Hongkong movie star #jackiechan ? 

I have probably walked by, under and through this building hundreds of times, yet this is the #firsttime I looked up and saw that it has a name - and quite an amazing #history as a #rickshaw depot or interchange back in the early 1900s (as you can see on the left pillar, it was constructed in 1903) now that I googled for it.

It has a beautiful #architecture as well, shame that I hadn't shoot its exterior a few evenings ago. To read more about its rather interesting history, read here: https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_485_2005-01-03.html

Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park is one of the largest parks in Singapore. Built in 1988,1 the park was revamped between 2009 and 2011 under the Active, Beautiful, Clean Waters (ABC Waters) Programme launched by PUB, Singaporeâ€™s National Water Agency.

 Subsequently, the park was reopened in 2012. Spanning 62 ha, it stretches along Ang Mo Kio Avenue 1 from Upper Thomson Road to Bishan Road.
An iconic feature of Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park is the naturalised river meandering through it. TheÂ three-kilometre waterway was converted from a concrete canal that channelled the Kallang River at the edge of the park. 

When the water level in the river is low, visitors can walk down the gentle river banks to get closer to the water; but during heavy rain, the parkland next to the river doubles up as a conveyance channel and carries excess water downstream.

Concrete slabs from the original canal have been stacked up to create a mound called Recycle Hill. An award-winning sculpture by Kelvin Lim Fun Kit titledÂ An Enclosure for a SwingÂ can be found at the top of the hill, where visitors can enjoy a good view of the entire park.

<309> â€œA Paradoxically Intriguing Templeâ€

Donâ€™t you find it paradoxical to see an ancient-looking 100-year-old Chinese temple surrounded by modern, high-rise buildings and located in a street named after Mohamed Sultan? Thatâ€™s so uniquely Singapore! 

The three big red Chinese characters on the walls of the temple are read â€œé³³å±±å¯ºâ€œ (FeÌ€ng shaÌ„nsiÌ€ in Mandarin or Hong San See in Hokkien), which can be literally translated as â€œTemple on Phoenix Hillâ€.

A Phoenix is a mystical bird that rises from the ashes. Coincidentally, the temple was restored to its glory ten years ago and had since gone on to win an Award of Excellence in the 2010 UNESCO Asia-Pacific Heritage Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation. Isnâ€™t the name befitting?

Whatâ€™s more, the temple worships the God of Fortune. I would have climbed up those steep steps without hesitation if I had known that earlier. Times are bad, every prayer counts. 

William

Remark: I was later informed by someone in my IG that the templeâ€™s main deity is not the God of Fortune. Alas! There goes my glimmer of hope that a prayer at this temple may bring me some fortune. (laughs).

A Love Story

Rediscovering Singapore has once again led me to a place I didn't know existed. This time, it brought me to the house of Tan Teng Niah. Little India is not short of colourful shophouses -- not unlike Kampong Gelam -- but the house of Tan Teng Niah stood out for me first and foremost with the Chinese engraving on its front door. "A Chinese residence in Little India?" That was the thought that first surfaced to my mind. In fact, I chanced upon this place, attracted by the colours and the inscription.

Written on the front door of this vividly vibrant house is a couplet referring to the wife of Tan Teng Niah, ç§€æ¾. While I did not manage to find any sources on an interpretation of the couplet, from my very basic Chinese understanding (hopefully not embarrassing my Chinese teachers), the couplet describes her wife as a beautiful (ç§€ä¸½æ™¯è‰²), pure and morally upright person (æ¾æŸæ“æŒ). While one can only guess why he made such a couplet, we may infer that Tan Teng Niah left the couplet on the door for the generations to come, to remember not just him but also his wife. He sounds like a romantic, loving husband if you were to ask me.

The W Hotel in Singapore has found itself at the centre of the latest instance of the culture war over LGBTQ rights in the country.

On Monday, 14 September, the five-star luxury hotel at Sentosa Cove posted a photo of gay influencer couple, fashion model Andee Chua @andeecys and Taiwanese YouTuber Hugo Liu @hugo_tw, on their social media. 

â€œWe are in the business of welcoming all and occasionally feature guests with their permission on our social platforms,â€ @wsingapore told Yahoo Lifestyle SEA. 

The hotel was promoting its staycations as travel restrictions remain in place because of the COVID-19 pandemic.

Take on life's challenges with BottomSlim. Their vision is to inspire and empower women through a renewed perspective on their bodies. Since 2008, they have been helping women transform into who they want to be. 

Their tagline promises the body you want without any painful surgeries. With the power of proprietary, clinically-tested slimming techniques and equipment, they provide one of the best Non-Surgical Alternative to Liposuction you can find in Singapore. Besides combating water retention to promote weight loss, they also provide a viable body contouring choice for those who can't exercise for medical reasons

We had planned a photowalk a couple of weeks back without realising it coincided with mid-autumn festival. It was only on the bus towards our destination then did we realise. How?

Before getting to the planned stop, we saw the moon big, low and round on the horizon, peeking from behind MBS. That's when my friend mentioned, "It's mid-autumn today!" Ecstatic, we quickly got off the bus laughing as we literally chased the moon. 

Perfect timing! ğŸ“¸

â€œWith a rich culture and amazing cuisine, Peranakans are known for their colourful heritage shophouses and intricate tiles. Beyond this row of vibrant architecture, Joo Chiat is great for food and a chill day of exploration!

To match these houses, I was reminded of the mooncakes from @thelapisplacesingapore, a creation that pushed boundaries and modernised the Kueh Lapis into a contemporary treat. The fusion of pastel-coloured snow skin on a rainbow-coloured Kueh Lapis that offers a twist to tradition â€“ and a new way for me to explore Singapore.â€

post_caption:
Guess the fish! ğŸ ğŸŸ

Indigenous to the lower Amazon region, primarily the ParnaÃ­ba River of Brazil, this mystery fish is found in flooded forest regions as well as in creeks and small tributaries. This fish typically is smaller and more stout in build. It has a shorter head and rounded snout. Also, it has a silvery gray body. Furthermore, a dark zigzag stripe runs along the lateral line from its gill to its tail. Above and below this dark line is a section that is not spotted, beyond which are many small, isolated black spots of varying size. 

Additionally, its dorsal fin is transparent with a large black blotch on the upper fin that does not extend down into the body. The caudal fin has vertical rows of dark brown spots that gives the appearance of striping. The anal, adipose, pectoral, and ventral fin also has these spots, but it is much paler in colour than on the caudal fin. Instead of scales, this fish has overlapping hard plates, known as scutes.
Overall, this fish can reach an adult size of slightly over 2 inches.

Stay tuned as the answer will be revealed tomorrow!

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sembawang Hot Spring Park

The entrance of Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Sembawang Hot Spring Park is located in SingaporeSembawang Hot Spring Park
Type	Hot spring
Location	Sembawang, Singapore
Nearest town	Yishun
Coordinates	1.4344Â°N 103.8224Â°ECoordinates: 1.4344Â°N 103.8224Â°E
Area	1.1 hectares (11,000 m2)
Opened	4 January 2020; 8 months ago
Owned by	NParks
Public transit access	 NS13  Yishun
Facilities	Hot spring
Website	Official website
The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring and a public park in Singapore.
It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, and its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser and Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership and potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle and bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020.
It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

-Vintage-

Taking a solo trip down to Little India alone last weekend to rediscover Singapore made me realise all the little things I overlook in life.

I had less pressure with time when I roamed around alone, and had the tenacity to speak to the people in the neighborhood. I learnt so much more when I spoke to the locals - Knowing why they came here for, what their struggles were (especially during this pandemic), their dreams and even the history of the places around us. And I truly miss traveling (solo) for the same reasons!

I donâ€™t usually post carousels, but these pictures truly piece together a beautiful set of stories of what Little India is all about - A mix of old and new, people, culture, art and history.

1. A box of vintage old films outside Sajeev Digital Studio

2. The studio upstairs, where foreign workers take portraits to send home the pictures for their families to matchmake them with potential wives

3. Sajeev Digital Studio from outside

4. An Indian foreign lady, named Mary, who works outside a pop-up stall at House of Tan Teng Niah (the colorful house 2 posts before). Sheâ€™s making prayer garlands using Jasmine, Rose, Orchid and Marigold and has been here for over 10 years

5. Massive mural which juxtaposes modern vehicles and the old-school way of transporting tiffins. Lorry as scale

6. Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple, Singaporeâ€™s oldest hindu temple that is dedicated to the goddess and destroyer of evil, Sri Veeramakaliamman or Kali. Early Migrant workers worship this goddess for safety in this new foreign land

This is the longest caption I have ever had, made with time, sweat, with sore legs and neck. Would appreciate it if you drop a comment below and tell me which photo caught your attention the most. Keep exploring, everyone!

This is the only village left in SG. Pretty unique and memorable one for many of the locals.
Me as a Malaysian, this is truly a nostalgia.
Like most early childhood memories, the rest of my kampung recollections are spare, fragmented, truncated; the equivalent of cinematic stills, with no soundtrack, no entertaining stories. Still, the few images that come to mind are vivid, enduring. The rough concrete floor of my grandmother's house; the splintered texture of the wooden walls, the chickens running free around the compound, the rickety chicken coop that I once tried to climb and nearly fell off the well with its column of cold damp air enclosed by stone.

Exploring the Garden City. While high-rise buildings can be found all over Singapore, the city has an abundance of urban greenery!

Lush with city parks, tropical nature reserves and botanical gardens, thereâ€™s something to be seen everywhere. Can you believe this picture was taken in Singapore?

Not many would expect to find a small, quiet village tucked away in the modern metropolis that is Singapore. Yet here stands Kampong Lorong Buangkok: Singaporeâ€™s ğ—¹ğ—®ğ˜€ğ˜ ğ—¸ğ—®ğ—ºğ—½ğ—¼ğ—»ğ—´ and a relic of a simpler and slower way of life.
.
In the minds of younger Singaporeans today, the kampong is a construct of oral history passed down from their parents and grandparents. Few have seen an actual kampong in the flesh. Far from being secluded, Kampong Lorong Buangkok is but a few metres away from the residential area of Yio Chu Kang. The zinc and wood houses of this little village stand in stark contrast to the concrete of its neighbouring HDB flats.
.
Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a rare gem: it is a part of Singaporeâ€™s living history, one which might soon be lost to the unceasing pace of development and renewal in this city-state. To say that I felt an overwhelming sense of nostalgia would have been excessively romantic. Like many of my millennial peers I grew up not knowing what kampong living was like. Visiting this little kampong is not simply akin to traveling back in time and gaining a glimpse of the kampong experience. It is about rediscovering Singapore â€“ the Singapore once inhabited by my grandparents. To be able to see how they might have once lived is truly a blessing: in rediscovering Singapore, I have also gained a deeper appreciation of my own roots.
.

Sajeev Digital Studio is more than a photography studio. Taken by Mr K Sajeev Lal, these photographs perform an important social function: they help South Asian male migrant workers find love back home in India and Sri Lanka! Mr Sajeev happily claims that he has a success rate of 100% ğŸ˜‰
.
An affable and jovial soul, Mr Sajeev gave me a tour of his studio and shared his personal story. I learned that he taught himself photography on a Yashica film camera when he was 15. He learnt film developing later, and adroitly turned his passion into a profession. Iâ€™m also glad that Mr Sajeev was game enough to pose for my photographs. As a photographer, I know that willing subjects are hard to come by. Mr Sajeevâ€™s willingness made the photo-taking experience so much more fun and imbued deeper meaning into these photographs that you see here.
.
One more thing that stood out for me was the thousands of portraits of migrant workers the adorned the walls of the little studio. These portraits formed an eclectic mosaic of untold stories. I took a moment to appreciate the fact that much of Singaporeâ€™s modern development would have been impossible without them, and that they too have suffered greatly because of the coronavirus. Looking at these portraits turned out to be a gentle reminder that we can do more to appreciate our migrant workers in our midst. I realised that rediscovering Singapore is not just about visiting local places of interest because we canâ€™t go overseas â€“ itâ€™s about rediscovering the different threads that form our magnificent social fabric, and how it is up to each and every one of us to make it stronger.
.

Masjid Sultan Mosqueâ 
Surrounded by rows of shophouses Masjid Sultan Mosque stands out with its massive golden domes and huge prayer hall, it is one of the must-see sites if youâ€™re in the historic Kampong Gelam district. â 
The mosque has a long history that goes back to 1824 when it was built for Sultan Hussein Shah, the first Sultan of Singapore. It has since passed through many development stages before becoming what it is today. â 
While youâ€™re there, check out the onion-shaped domes as each dome base is decorated with glass bottle ends donated by lower-income Muslims during its construction so that all Muslims, not just the rich, could contribute. â 
In 1975, the mosque was gazetted as a national monument, it has been a focal point for the Muslim Community. â 
To find out more about the mosque, click on the link http://sultanmosque.sg/about-us/sultan-mosque-historyâ

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

The good old days at Tee Seng Store. Putting everything together, hope u like it...

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practiseÂ qigongÂ before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampungÂ spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

Grasses and weeds have a role in the ecosystem. There are many that are pretty too! ğŸ’š

Hydrocotyle verticillata, also known as whorled pennywort, whorled marshpennywort or shield pennywort, is a flowering plant found in South and North America and the West Indies. The creeping plants with unusual leaves give it its common names. It grows in places that are marshy, boggy, and wet. Hydrocotyle verticillata is used in aquaria, where it is undemanding but prefers a good substrate, and at least moderate light. It benefits from additional carbon dioxide.(Nature's #aircleaner!) (Source: Wikipedia)

ã€Ang Mo Kio #3 - Fried Riceã€‘
Where do you get your fried-rice-fix? Where is your favourite _zhichar_ or western food stall? If you are craving for some old school western food and fried rice, you have to visit Yummy Western stall located at Blk 409 Ang Mo Kio Avenue 10 (avoid peak hours if you are in a hurry). The chef cooking this fried rice has been in the business for about 20 years - no wonder the fried rice tastes so good and full of â€˜wok heiâ€™ flavour! Truly satisfying!

This week, #dabaogram tried a new dimension of food plating with a floral touch. Greens like cucumbers and parsley were added to give it a refreshing look and feel . We reshaped the side dishes and positioned them like an arrow pointing upwards. Can you see it?  Finally, we used some of the accompanying chilli sauce to add some vibrant colour to the dish. Viola!

We would like to thank Yummy Western for preparing such delicious fried rice and western food. According to the owner, all dishes were marinated using a  special curated sauce. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own â€˜dabaogramâ€™ at home. 

Next weekâ€™s makeover dish is our favourite for Ang Mo Kio. Stay tuned cosâ€™ you wonâ€™t want to miss it, see ya!

The setting of this supermarket in that era was to allow Singaporeans to buy groceries and other daily necessities at affordable prices because of the high inflation rate back then.
