SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Katong / Joo Chiat precinct

In Katong Joo Chiat area, you can discover conserved heritage shophouses with Peranakan culture or influence /designs.

Although this area is very well known for it's colourful street, Koon Seng Road, Katong Joo Chiat precinct, has other good attractions as well.

1. Teong Theng Co is a old school crafted rattan based furniture maker that has 70 years of history in Joo Chiat.  This is a good time to rediscover, some of our heritage shops and at the same time, feels the nostalgic vibes

2. China Collection (antique) shop is painted blue and white and this Chinese shop house  has now turn itself into a modern building with a minimal twist. Those who likes minimal design will appreciate the paint work

3. I couldnt resist taking a shot of this old school hair salon, everytime I pass by

4. Rumah Bebe in Katong is a Peranakan heritage boutique, a school, a bake shop and also a mini museum. I simply love the interior (more like exterior) decor.

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival everyone! May your personal and professional life be blessed with moments of joy and happiness! 

Come over to Qian Hu Fish Farm and celebrate with us!

Also, head over to our ecommerce store at https://www.qianhushop.sg/ today! 

https://www.qianhushop.sg/ offers you a wide range of aquarium and pet accessories!
 
Here are some interesting findings about the festival:
According to some experts, the Mid-Autumn Festival was traditionally a time to express gratitude to the gods. It is also a time of year that the moon is at its brightest. This explains why lunar legends have always been attached to the celebration. 

I trust many of us are aware of the story of Chang Er, the wife of a merciless king who drank the elixir of immortality he had intended to drink, so as to save her people from his tyrannical rule.
It is believed that she has ascended to the moon upon her brave act, and has been worshipped by the Chinese as a Moon Goddess ever since.

Many would enjoy the occasion by attending moon-gazing parties. Family and friends would sit in gardens lit by the soft glow of paper lanterns, sip tea and nibble on mooncakes.

Children in particular love this festival as they get to tote lanterns. In the past, there were only traditional lanterns with wax candles that are made from paper. Today, there are also plastic, battery-operated versions.

Mooncakes are the main highlight of the Mid-Autumn Festival. It is believed that they helped to free Yuan China from Mongol rule, after rebels organised an uprising by passing messages hidden in these mooncakes.

Today, there are not only traditional flavours with lotus seed paste and egg yolk but also snowskin versions filled with everything from chocolate to durian. They are best enjoyed with a strong, palate-cleansing cup of Chinese tea.

Old is indeed gold and time truly stood still here at Tong Ah Eating House the moment you stepped into the restaurant with all the interior setup and food that they are serving, which hasnâ€™t changed much from many years ago. Instead of going for their extra crispy toast, we decided to get their French toast that comes with a slab of melting butter on top the toast with their own homemade moreish kaya by the side. The kaya is slightly different from the rest as theirs are eggier with a clumpy texture that is not as smooth as others. While the setup might not appeal to many, the quality of the traditional brewed Nanyang coffee more than makes up for it, the aroma and thickness will awaken any senses. I truly hope that the charm of this old-world heritage establishment remains as it is for many years to come to contrast all the modernization that is happening now to the F&B industry.

Have you gotten it right? ğŸ˜†ğŸ˜œ

The answer is Leopard Corydoras, which is commonly known as Corydoras julii! Great job to those who guessed correctly! For the rest of us, nice try! Letâ€™s all try harder again in the next round! 

Corydoras julii is not demanding and tolerates a range of initial water parameters. Water can be slightly acidic to slightly alkaline, with soft to medium-hard water hardness. The substrate in this fishâ€™s tank must be soft, as it will scavenge the bottom for bits of food. Sand or small and smooth gravel is suitable. Driftwood is recommended, as well as other items that can serve as hiding places. Plants are also essential. Floating plants are often used to dim the lighting, as this fish does not appreciate bright lights.

Furthermore, Corydoras julii accepts most food. You can offer it sinking tablets or pellets as their primary diet. Live foods like brine shrimp, daphnia, and bloodworms can be offered to supplement their diet. Because it is a nocturnal, it is best to feed it before lights are turned off.

Lastly, Corydoras julii is best kept in a school of a minimum of four or more. It gets along well with small catfish and small peaceful fish. Possible tankmates include small members of the tetra family, rasboras, dwarf cichlids, danios and other small community fish. You should avoid any large or aggressive fish.

Trithemis aurora, the crimson marsh glider, is a species of #dragonfly in the family Libellulidae. It is a medium-sized dragonfly that is commonly found in weedy tanks and ponds, marshes, channels, and slow flowing streams and rivers in the lowlands and mid-hills. It breeds in streams, rivers, canals, ponds and tanks. (Source: Wikipedia)

Recovery Walk along East coast for Food & Coffee. Past by a few heritages establishments. Guillemard Camp (1969-2003) -  home to the First Singapore Infantry Regiment. One of the oldest furniture shops in Singapore, that specialises in classic rattan furniture. A old styled coffee and bakes that is permanently closed. A new Starbucks outlet at colonial-era formerÂ Joo Chiat Police Station that was built in 1928. And lastly, Katong Shopping Centre - the first air-conditioned mall in Singapore. Now well-known for its Chicken rice at the food court in its basement level.

Can you see the moon tonight?

Tomorrow night, 1st October, will be a full moon night. The moon will be at its roundest and biggest, also known as the Harvest Moon. It is also the Mid Autumn Mooncake festival.

Enjoy your moon photography tomorrow.

This photo of the moon was shot with a Sony G-Master 70-200mm lens. Shutter speed was set at 1/125, aperture at f/8 and ISO200.

Appreciating the hidden gems of Little India, Joo Chiat and Chinatown 

ğŸ“Little India
â€¢Little India - Once a place for racecourse, cattle herders and brick kilns. Now one of Singaporeâ€™s most vibrant districts.
â€¢Little India Street Art / Five Foot Way -Explore Little India's rich multicultural history through its vibrant walls. â˜ğŸ½On a side note, did you notice that 5-foot-way? the roofed continuous walkway commonly found in front of shops, the name refers to the width of the passageway. These walkways were meant to protect pedestrians from the hot tropical sun as well as rain.
â€¢Deepavali Street Light Up - One of the major cultural festivals in Singapore, Deepavali (also known as â€œDiwaliâ€ or the â€œFestival of Lightsâ€) is a celebration that marks the triumph of good over evil. 
â€¢House of Tan Teng Niah - windows of the unique and colorful Chinese Villa that was built in 1900

ğŸ“Kampong Gelam
â€¢Streetside Barbershop
â€¢Spiral Staircases of Bugis - These external pre-cast concrete staircases first made their appearance at the rear of shophouses from the mid-1920s. Their introduction facilitated an important regular routine for households and residents living in the shophouses â€“ the collection of night-soil. Night-soil is a euphemism for human faeces. The term came about, as human waste was collected in buckets in the silence of the night and sometimes, soil was used as a cover. A night-soil carrier would enter the alleys behind the shophouses and climb these spiral staircases to each storey. That was where buckets filled with night-soil were placed.

ğŸ“Joo Chiat
â€¢Peranakan Shophouses of Joo Chiat

Old and New meet at the ever changing, glam Kampong Glam.

Pigeons famous, Kampong Glam is the Muslim center of Singapore, and is traditionally home to mosques, carpet shops, and Middle Eastern cuisine, while more recently the area has seen a surge in boutique cocktail bars and funky restaurant openings. Sightseers will enjoy the picturesque streets with their beautifully restored shophouses, while shoppers are in for a treat with a selection of Singaporeâ€™s best offbeat boutiques selling cult labels and vintage clothing.

(Oh yes, after only 200 shots her majesty the glam pigeon quickly flew into place which is appreciated by me.)

@hubandspokecafe is a very young new ground level cafÃ© located just minutes away from @changiairport Terminal 2. 

Most of the cafÃ©'s offerings are western-style brunch, pastas, salads, breakfast toasts, and the usual coffee/tea offerings. What stands out and to keep with modern times, is that they have bubble tea offerings too. 

This isn't a food review though, but just to publicise such a place exists. 

Also, they accept your own cups and bottles if you wish to use your own to-go cup in replacement of the single-use cups they offer for cold drinks! ğŸ’š 

The cafÃ© also has showers (coming soon)! ğŸš¿ğŸ›€

Right now, the cafÃ© has great views of the main road, which includes glimpses of buses passing by as they exit the Terminal 2 Passenger Building. ğŸšŒğŸšŒ

One incentive to visit this cafÃ© is if you cycle along the Park Connector Network from East Coast Park via the Jurassic Mile. Bicycle racks are available, with a bicycle rental service by Go Cycling as well. ğŸš²

There is a vending machine selling items from cables to wet tissues and face masks.

If you are going to take a walk from @jewelchangiairport , it's about 2kâ€“3k+ steps each way via the Terminal 2â€“Jewel link bridge. 

Once any travel bubble or when the SQ tours set in, hopefully we will see more traffic at this cornerside cafÃ©. It's not that accessible unless you park at the South Carpark near Terminal 2 or the Carpark 2A and walk in (if it's open?).

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sago Lane / Sago Street, in Chinatown

Sago Lane (and Sago Street) gets its name from the many sago factories in the area in mid-1800s Singapore. However, Sago Lane is more famous (or infamous) for another reason - its death houses.

In the pastÂ when most Chinese immigrants lived in Chinatown area, the terminally ill would go to a death house where they literally awaited their fate â€“ death.

Now the street has just been revitalised with new arch Chinatown signs and Chinese orientated shelters. 

Of course the main attraction is still the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple. Even if you are not there to pray, the lanterns or lighting (during some festive periods) are an attraction itself.

Given the most depressing covid period, any nice temple or street lighting certainly cheers us up and gives us hope. ğŸ™

This is Sajeev. He is the owner of Sajeev Digital Studio in Little India, a cramped but friendly space where the walls are lined with thousands of past portraits heâ€™s taken over the years.

His main clientele consists of foreign workers from India and Sri Lanka who send their portraits back home so their families can help in the matchmaking process and search for their future wives. He says his business has been affected by Covid as new foreign workers have stopped entering the country. Still, he was gracious enough to give me a quick tour of his studio, observe a shoot, and discuss a bit of his unique story and business model.

post_caption:
And on the right side of the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple lies Sago Lane (Street of the Dead). 
In the past, the street was much longer and was home to funeral parlours or death houses. 
The lane's famous Chinese death houses came into existence in the late 19th century. This was the place where people near death will be left to die.
As people were superstitious and believed that it was inauspicious to die in their own home, many chose to pay a small fee to stay in these death houses to wait for their time.
Sago Lane after all is not just a lane, it is a History in itself.

A kampong's beauty
.
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singaporeâ€™s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each otherâ€™s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkokâ€™s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

Alone but not lonely.

Can you spot 3 people who are alone (and in their own world) in this photo?

Personally, i'm a huge proponent of #metime. Spending time alone is actually a good thing as the relationship you have with yourself is the most important one in your life. 

According to research, dedicating some me time to yourself has benefits such as increased productivity, happiness, gratitude and empathy. It also allows you to recharge your batteries, slow down and take your mind off from the hustle and bustle of everyday life. 

When was the last time you really spent quality me time with yourself?

A different experience exploring in the dark and coming up close to animals at night. You can only do this at the Night Safari, the world's first nocturnal zoo! It was the kids' first time at the Night Safari and we had a great time there! There were moments where it was pitch dark when we were on the tram and our senses were heightened so we could spot, hear or smell something nearby. 

Swipe to check out our video where we had close encounters with hyenas and cheetahs! 

The kids were exhausted after we exited the Night Safari because it was close to their bedtime but they agreed that it was an awesome and refreshing experience to see animals at night. We missed the Creatures of the Night Show because it was full but we will be back again!

Discover this hidden gem at Fort Canning Park, the next popular Instagram-worthy place. 

The Fort Canning Tree Tunnel is an underground crossing with spiral staircase that links Dhoby Ghaut to the park. If you look up, you can see a circle of lush greenery.

When it comes to Mid-Autumn Festival, the first thing that comes to my mind will be the moon cakes. My family and I will love to get a box or two of the moon cakes from the shops in Chinatown. At home, we will sit together in front of the television and enjoy the moon cakes with a cup of green tea. We also love to meet up with my parents, sisters and nieces in their home or in a park for lantern walk. Well, for me I will love to go down to Chinatown to take photos of the beautiful Mid-Autumn festival street decorations and walk the streets of Chinatown to get the feel of the festival there.

Something I've always enjoyed about night photography is experimentation with long exposures. I love the effect I get with clouds, moving water and of course, light trails with moving objects.

To envision with your mind's eye and then be able capture what the eye is unable to physically see is truly satisfying. Using photography to capture more than just light - capture time and space.

[ Who Painted The Tree? ]

I have visited Katong Park and walked pass this tree more than times than I could count but I have never realised the beauty of it until recently someone told me that there is a "RainbowğŸŒˆ" tree in this park.

As I walked and looked closer, the tree does look like someone painted it, but it is actually naturally gorgeous. From the #NParks signboard I learned that this colourful tree that features rainbow coloured streaks along its trunk is called Rainbow Eucalyptus. As the tree sheds its outer bark at different times to reveal the neon green bark underneath, over time, this layer is exposed to air and ages into different colors â€” from green to blue to purple to orange to maroon before finally falling off the tree.

This colourful tree is also the only one of its kind in Singapore and has been listed by the National Parks as a Heritage Tree. If you are the type that like to chase after rainbows,Â it is located at Katong Park, near the Fort Road exit of East Coast Park.

p.s. No tree was harmed in the making of this series

[Kampong Gelam Precinct] - The Iconic Zam Zam food stall

Re-discovering Kampong Gelam again starting with food and its people.Â  Rediscovering is about documenting great people working hard amidst the pandemic to serve us with great food with passion.

You should not miss out the friendly people from Singapore Zam Zam. It is established in 1908 and one of the most popular Indian-Muslim restaurant in Singapore. They are well-known for their murtabak (in photo), Roti prata, Nasi biryani and many other dishes for over a century.Â  The best part about this placeÂ  is that their staff are very friendly and engaging. Instead of focusing on the things that don't matter, get obsessed with who you're becoming, where you're going and all of the amazing things you're going to accomplish!

More than ever, this year in which everything has been on pause, has been the best time to do everything you always wanted to do! Your personal projects, your side-hustles, etc!

To think that there is only 3 months left to this year is crazy, but donâ€™t let that time pass by, use it wisely and create!

I was strolling around Sago Lane and its surrounding area a week back. It used to be the home for several funeral parlours or death houses. As I walk on the Sago Lane closer to the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, a gust of wind blew strongly, shaking the red lanterns hung around the temple. It felt a bit spooky, but it also brought in a sense of amazement in me.

Continuing after, I went to the adjacent side of Sago Lane, called Sago Street. It was named that way because during the 1800s, there were many sago factories there. I also learned that it used to house a number of brothels around the late 19th century.Â 

I explored into some alleyways in wonder and in one moment, I realized that I got to pick up my camera and shoot.

When we are able to go back traveling again to Singapore, go visit Chinatown! It is an amazing precinct rich with history :)

Shopping for Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

During its peak, up to 300 people visited the hot spring daily. On 1 March 2002, it was closed for two months while upgrading & improvement works were carried out to the area around the spring, which had become sodden & muddy. Littering had also become a problem because of the increased numbers of visitors. The former dirt track leading to the spring was paved with cement, & lined with bougainvillea bushes & high fences to ensure the security of the air base. Drainage pipes were also installed. Mindef, which owns the land, allows public access between 7 am and 7 pm daily, free-of-charge. When the spring reopened on 1 May 2002, more than 100 people visited the site despite the afternoon drizzle. At the same time, some new free-hold condominiums were built in the surrounding area; one of the developments, built by the property arm of F&N in 2001, is called Seletaris, named after the company's former mineral water.

In July 2005, a Business Times reader proposed that the authorities should explore the possibility of tapping the geothermal heat that lies many miles under Sembawangâ€”similar to the project in South Australia's Cooper Basinâ€”in order to aid Singapore's reliance on oil and gas. The proposal was not acted upon.

 As of 2014, the well can still be seen locked inside a red-brick enclosure with a steel gate, & its geothermal heat can be felt outside the building. Some plastic chairs, pails and mini-tubs kindly donated by visitors are stored at the perimeter of the compound, which has a makeshift shed in one corner. A caretaker, paid for by Mindef, takes care of the place to maintain its overall cleanliness, but there is no toilet on location. The hot spring is less frequented nowadays but remains rustic for rural & suburban families to discover & explore.

post_caption:
The Mid-Autumn Festival means more than just lanterns and mooncakes to me, it's a celebration of tradition, culture and time spent with the family. 

As per tradition, we spent a full day at Chinatown, amidst the smells and the sounds we ate a hearty lunch and strolled passed the usual routes. Bought somethings here and there and visited the Buddha's tooth temple.  Following that we returned home to a comforting and lively family gathering at grandma's place in celebration of the Mid-Autumn Festival. 

It's hard to get time with everyone in our hustle bustle life but just a simple meal with the ones you love is all that you need. 

Photos are in the back after the video. 
@chinatown_festivals

Went to @gardensbythebay a few weeks ago before my injury. It was my first time visiting the Cloud Forest. I also brought along the @samsung_sg Galaxy Tab S7 to do some sketching at the Cloud Forest and also try out the Samsung tablet that I got.
.
The battery life is pretty good, it lasted the entire day and the pen can be used for drawing without charging. The sensitivity is on-point too. I used Clip Studio and Adobe Sketch for the sketches during my visit.
.
The cloud forest visit itself was a nice experience as well. I think I spent about two hours in it, the mosses reminded me of the trip to Kibune earlier this year.
.

Since the signage reads â€œSupreme Pork Chop Riceâ€, thereâ€™s just no way I will order anything else besides their pork chop rice. Situated in the basement of a nondescript building along Beach Road, the stall is housed in an area with other F&B outlets. Hydrotherapy
Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 Â°C (160 Â°F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

Here are some food and product photos that I have shot and taught in my smartphone food photography workshops.

Recently, small grocers, chefs and home-based businesses approached me for product photography, mostly related to food and fresh produce.

With no photography budget, I said I will teach them instead, with a minimal fee, which is the simplest cost effective way to do it. 

Use your smartphone.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, almost all businesses especially small self owned ones are hard hit by loss of revenues.

Nevertheless, these business owners know that visuals are important for their business growth and social media marketing.

If you are one of them and want to learn how to create product images with no frills, drop me an email at info@carolinepang.com

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

The old #shophouses in Singapore are an important part of our heritage and they are a delight to photograph. Along Duxton road, you can find rows of two- and three-storey shophouse units that are beautifully-restored.

One great example is the former Six Senses Duxton, a boutique hotel that took up eight restored shophouses. Sadly, they have ceased operations not long ago.

#FunFact: Duxton Road had a seedy reputation for its opium dens, gambling dens & brothels during the early 19th and 20th centuries!

Check out our blog #linkinbio for more fun facts & secret insights about Singapore >> www.monsterdaytours.com/travel-tips-and-guides

Have you managed to shoot those stunning night scenes, light trails, smooth silky waters and more?

Check out my night photography workshop on Link in Bio.

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

Went back to Jewel again this weekend and visited Canopy Bridge (not part of Canopy Park btw)! The bridge gives you a close up view of the Jewel waterfall five stories up! Other than the close-up and height, the novelty of the bridge also lies in the fact that it is translucent (I say translucent as I couldn't see thru clearly due to reflection) so my younger girl was a bit scared ğŸ˜… Oh, and we really like the effect of the mist when we enter the bridge ğŸ˜„
.
Actually I had thought  the bridge would let us walk around the waterfall but you only get to walk past the waterfall and it's really quite a short bridge. If you don't linger to take photos, you'll be at the other end within a minute ğŸ˜‚
.
Tickets cost us $3.60 each. Guess I didn't really mind as I bought the tics with the 55% discount they are having for Jewel attractions (only till 31 August). I probably wouldn't pay full price for this ğŸ˜… But still, we had a good ten minute fun enjoying the view and having wobbly knees ğŸ˜„ How did your weekend go? ğŸ˜‰

Like many Singaporeans, Iâ€™m a great fan of Mustafa Centre. This place started its journey as a makeshift shop set up by Mohamed Mustafa and his son to sell ready-made garments on Campbell Lane. Over the years, Mustafa Centre was gradually built up from one shop to two large buildings along Syed Alwi Road. It was only in 2003 that Mustafa Centre became a 24-hour shopping centre, now with some adjustments to its operating hours. Not to worry â€“ you can still buy almost anything there!
Â 
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your favourite part of Mustafa Centre with #SingapoRediscovers.

Last workshop in our September school holiday series! Spend meaningful time with your child and teach them the importance of preserving Mother Earth ğŸŒ through this beeswax wrap making workshop!â£â£
â£â£
Date: Saturday, 12 September 2020â£â£
Time: 10.30 - 11.30â£â£
Instructor: Clara Simanjuntakâ£â£
â£â£
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695â£â£
â£â£
Course Fee: SGD45/parent & 1 childâ£â£
Price inclusive of tools and materialsâ£â£
â£â£
Clara Simanjuntak is Nyananyana Eco-fashion founder and designer. The clothing and accessories brand was conceptualised in Singapore in 2011. After a long journey of sourcing and research about all natural fabrics and dyes from plants, the brand finally launched in 2017 in Jakarta. Nyananyana is currently based in Singapore.â£â£
â£â£
She conducts workshops to introduce natural dye as a form of Nyananyanaâ€™s green campaign.â£â£
â£â£
Clara also the founder of Jakarta Museum Playdate, community of parents and children where she visits and eco friendly themed workshop in museums.â£â£
â£â£
Beeswax wraps have become more popular as eco-friendly household items, replacing cling wraps that are non-biodegradable. In this hands-on workshop, participants will learn the use of beeswax wraps, materials needed and how to make a wrap step-by-step.â£â£
â£â£
By using certified organic fabric with natural dye and organic forest beeswax, say goodbye to single-use plastic covers. Each participant will get to bring back one piece of their self made beeswax.â£
â£

-The Deities and the Dead-

I have always walked by this temple and never thought much about it apart from its distinctive Tang Dynasty design in our urban environment.

Rediscovering Singapore is how I adapt to this new change (or new normal)! While finding local iconic spots to shoot in new perspective, I discovered that the Sago Lane beside this temple was known to be the â€œDead People Streetâ€, as the terminally ill would go to these houses to wait for death. 

The business-minded Chinese would make the upper floors of the shophouses the â€œdeath houseâ€, while the ground floor serves as a funeral parlour, and that stretch of road would be the road to send off the dead!

How many of us truly know the history and cultural heritage of these newly developed places? Anyone know more spots like this to share with me, or you would like me to explore more?

Visited the National Gallery last weekend and what an experience it was!

Loved the beautiful architecture preserved from yester-years which tells of Singapore's history from the times when we were under British rule to when we strived for independence.

I can't believe it's only been 55 years since the times of the night soil man and kampung dwellings to today's cosmopolitan city and high rise HDB flats. ğŸ¤¯ Its amazing how things have changed and I can't imagine living through all these changes in a single lifetime.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Ang Mo Kio in Hokkien literally means the â€˜red-haired manâ€™s bridgeâ€™, whereÂ ang moÂ is a colloquial term for a Caucasian person. The name makes reference to the bridge over Kallang River in the area, built by Johnson Turnball Thomson, Government Surveyor of the Straits Settlement from 1841 to 1853. Another saying was that there were 9 bridges connecting the rural area back in those days, earning it the name â€˜Kow Tiao Kioâ€™ or Hokkien for â€˜9 bridgesâ€™.

The town was largely uninhabited until the rubber boom in the beginning of the 20th century, which brought cultivation and habitation to the Chinese district. Ang Mo Kio comprised mainly farms and attap houses scattered among rubber estates.

Lantern Installation: â€œRolling in Abundanceâ€
(Supported by 78JO)
Produced by Hong Kong artist Sunny Tam of the collectible label, 78JO in collaboration with the Sun Yat Sen Nanyang Memorial Hall, â€œRolling in Abundanceâ€ is an outdoor installation featuring four large roly-poly fish lanterns. In Chinese culture, fishes (â€œyuâ€) symbolise completeness and abundance, as it is a homonym for the Mandarin word for â€œabundanceâ€ (â€œyuâ€). The rounded nature of the design is doubly symbolic, as roundness (â€œyuanâ€) also sounds similar to the Mandarin word for â€œreunionâ€ (â€œtuan yuanâ€), and pays homage to the full and bright mid-autumn moon. 

â€œRolling in Abundanceâ€ utilises wordplay to present traditional beliefs and values in a modern context, and encourages deeper understanding and appreciation of the beauty of the Chinese language. More importantly, in these trying times, the installation embodies our hope for more abundant years to come, and gives thanks as we reunite with families and loved ones during Phase 2 of Singaporeâ€™s circuit breaker period

Date: 15 September - 11 October
Time: 10.00am - 9.00pm (daily)

Spring Well
â€œVillage of Hot Waterâ€
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1909, a Chinese merchant named Seah Eng Keong, the son of Chinese pioneer Seah Liang Seah, discovered hot springs in his pineapple estate in Sembawang. The three springs were channelled into one, so that the water would be conveniently concentrated in one area. A well was built along with the spring, which became popular with the villagers, who frequently sought the waters for their supposed healing powers. The spring's fame spread, resulting in the village becoming known as Kampong Ayer Panas, which means "Village of Hot Water" in Malay.

Soft drinks firm Fraser & Neave (F&N) acquired the site in 1922, & set up a bottling plant at nearby Semangat Ayer to tap the mineral water, which they labelled Seletaris. During the Second World War, the spring's flow was temporarily interrupted when a bomb fell near the well during a Japanese air raid over Singapore in 1942. After the fall of Singapore, the Japanese military seized the place & converted it into recreational thermal baths (onsen).

The hot spring was frequented by gamblers in 1960, who took "good luck" baths before the start of horse races. That same year, the villagers urged the authorities to develop the area into a spa-like onsen tourist resort. However, F&N shelved the suggestion after geologists could not trace the source of the spring water. In 1967, the proposal of the spa surfaced again, when F&N proposed plans for the development of a bathhouse, restaurants, a miniature golf course & even a nature reserve. However, the plans did not materialize, so the hot spring remained untouched & forgotten.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Reflection of Joo Chiatâ€™s best ambassadorsÂ 

Rediscovery is about having a good listening ear  and keen observation of the place and people.

Joo Chiat is a place with a rich history. We often see elderly around. Some leisurely walking around while others cycle. What is unique is the friendliness of the people. I was there twice recently. On both occasions, I have had elderly (residents or former residents) who came to chitchat with me about the heritage of the place as well as interesting places to shoot. They seem to be the best ambassadors of the place - For their knowledge and their part in the history of this place- to help us rediscover Singapore.

This is a reflection ( literally) of the elderly from Joo Chiat with the colorful peranakan house

Directions

COVID-19 took the world by its ankles and lifted it off, tumbling downhill since the start of spring 2020. With the much reduced number of daily reported cases and Phase 3 in sight, Singaporeans have slowly returned to the streets of Singapore. While travelling overseas is still not an option on the table, we may contribute to the economy and support the local tourism industry that has been hit hard by the pandemic.

Here in Little India, preparations for Deepavali are underway. Hindu devotees may be found purchasing festive goods in Little India, the streets are installed with festive lightings and are ready for the festival of light. As a whole, the nation seems ready to move away from the shadow cast by COVID-19, and instead look forward to celebrating Deepavali.

During my trips to Little India in the past 2 weeks, I noticed these beautiful road signages that seem to be unique to Little India. From my research, I found that these signages can be found on several streets: Campbell Lane, Buffalo Road, Kerbau Road, Veerasamy Road, Serangoon Road and Upper Weld Road. Despite my best efforts to collect them all, I've only managed to photograph 4 of the 6 that I've listed. Locating the Serangoon Road sign left me with unglam tanned lines that shall remain on me for sometime. Perhaps in this case, rediscovering Singapore may lead you to locating this road sign that has slipped through my fingers.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok, built in 1956, is probably the last Kampong in mainland Singapore

I decided to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks, who are always obliging for a chat or phototaking

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my late uncle house's  in Pasir Ris Kampong

The kids here run freely and love it here. The 70 year old uncle I spoke to, says the family always like to gather at their mom's house on weekend

You can see herbs, mango, banana and even a coca tree here.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone, to experience this kampong way of life. 

Just make sure you respect their privacy if they are not keen to have their pictures taken.

Note: Permissions have been granted to take the pictures of the residents, in their house compound, from afar.

Do you knowğŸ˜¯: There's more than just golden ornaments and sweets during Deepavali. Observe the grand Silver Chariot Procession and you'll see that Deepavali is a humble celebration between family and friends as well. Comprising priests, devotees and volunteers, the procession begins its journey from Singapore's oldest Hindu temple every year a week before Deepavali before making its way into Singapore's heartlands with the simple aim of allowing Hindu families to offer their prayers to the presiding deity. #singaporediscovers @stb_sg

Try something new this weekend and go for a walking trail with your family! MacRitchie Reservoir is a water catchment area in central Singapore. Filled with wildlife, you can take a nice relaxing walk around the lake and away from the noise of city life. In Malaysia, Sungei Lembing offers a beautiful spot to watch the sunrise as well as a majestic waterfall. Bring your family to catch the rainbow that forms every morning.Â Â â£
â£
Over in Cameron Highlands, Malaysia, cooling temperatures await in a place known as the Mossy Forest. The fog in the air guarantees a magical atmosphere for you and family, as well as the perfect setting for an impromptu photoshoot if you feel up to it!â£

First geocache - Easter Egg [GC8T562]
ğŸ— They always say - first step is the hardest. 

So, we take a baby step to start an adventure. 

09Oct2020 (Pandemic ~ Covid19 ğŸ¦ ) That was D day - Childrenâ€™s Day, a School holiday in Singapore. Probably the best reason to not we procrastinate any further. 

We decided to get out and explore this day with E, our daughter, instead of coping at home studying and mugging for exams. Mugging a word often used for Singaporean children to go on drilling for their exams. ğŸ˜„Muggle used in #harrypotter to describe someone who doesnâ€™t know anything related magic and the wizardry world. Often used in Singapore to describe anyone who is not geocaching. ğŸ¤£ 

Ok I went off-point. 

ğŸ—’ We started with a short walk along the footpath towards the treasure following the description. Surrounded by overgrown creepy green leaves, it took us about ten minutes (normal pace) to reach the coordinates. 

Walking with masks in this horrible humidity and heat was another challenge. 

This, however, did not deter Eâ€™s enthusiasm. She loves treasure hunting and detective stories. #geocaching will be the best family bonding activity, well, a family hobby. Besides, we had a pretty heavy lunch (steamboat/ hotpot!), so it was time to walk it off. ğŸ¤—

Soon we reached the exact spot but we just cannot find it!

Trying to clear some soil by rubbing our shoes on the ground, yes(!) we are neat freaks and too virus conscious nowadays. Everything seemed to have a layer of germs on it. ğŸ¤ª

After fifteen minutes of poking and brushing the tips of the grass with my slippers, we decided to message the owner of the cache.

Funnily enough, while waiting for the reply, G being the man as he always is, decided to dig into some suspicious ground and found the Yellow Egg! It was a lovely â€œEaster-eggâ€ Hunt! ğŸ¥³ 

We are grateful to find our first cache in this little adventure of our mundane life. ğŸ™ğŸ» looking forward to more little hunts in the future. 

Meanwhile, stay safe and mask on! ğŸ˜·

Of Murals and We-fies

The Gelam Gallery rejuvenates the back alleys of Kampong Gelam, where glamorous pictures are taken against the backdrop of paintings, bright and colourful. These murals bring new life to the historical site, engaging the new generation with the past. New memories of this place are created, tying generations of Singaporeans together.

While Kampong Gelam used to be the enclave for the Malay community in Singapore, and in the present where much of the district's flavour revolves around the Malay heritage still, places like the Gelam Gallery act as an avenue to attract the nation to visit Kampong Gelam and learn about its history and the Malay culture. By giving it a fresh paint of life, it ensures continuity in the knowledge of its history.

Warehouse
.
.
.
.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

CHIJMES (pronounced "chimes", acronym definition: Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus and â€˜MESâ€™ was added intentionally to make it sounds like chimes) is a historic building complex in Singapore.â£
â£â£
The complex was used as a Catholic convent since 1852, with an acquired Caldwell House which was constructed in 1840â€“1841, an acquired Convent Orphanage house in 1855, the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus Chapel in 1904 and an acquired hotel complex for the girls' school in 1933. The Caldwell House, currently a wedding venue, and the Gothic-style chapel, renamed as CHIJMES Hall, currently a function hall and also a wedding venue, have both been gazetted as national monuments. The complex has been restored in 1996 for commercial purposes as a dining, shopping and entertainment centre with ethnic restaurants, shops and a function hall, providing a backdrop for musicals, recitals, theatrical performances and weddings. (Source: Wikipedia)â£â£

A few years back, from a small stall at a pop-up food village with his iconic Durian Creme BrÃ»lÃ©e, that was my first encounter with Chef Deming. His love, passion and advocacy for local Singapore food can be seen, felt and tasted at The Quarters. Beyond and above, his forward-tasting and thinking in local Singapore cuisine started a new wave of modern Singapore (Mod-Sin) cuisine through a fusion of traditional and modern cuisine, in a communal dining known as The Quarters Experience. 

More than just preserving and holding on to our local Singapore food cuisine and culinary, Chef Deming belongs to a group of young food entrepreneurs leading the way to preserve, uphold and spread an important segment of our Singaporeâ€™s intangible cultural heritage and our love obsession with food. 

The time is now to start your own #SingapoRediscovers #sgfood journey! Visit @thequarterssg and rediscover a new world of Mod-Sin cuisine.

Iâ€™ve been to South Beach couple of times in the past but only for dining. This time round after a night of exploration, I realized there is so much history and innovation behind the place - it really is an attraction on its own!

We chanced upon this corner and love how it captures the blend of heritage with modern architecture - the new building set against the old SAF NCO Club and the arched entrance of the old block 9. 

Singapore has been progressing at such a fast pace with our landscape always  changing with new developments, so all the more I appreciate the restoration work by South Beach to keep a part of our history alive. 

Hope by sharing what I see though my amateur eyes, you may be inspired to rediscover Singapore too ã€°ï¸

Travel photography is not just about shooting nice places or destinations or good food. 

It is about connecting viewers to the uniqueness of the place, itâ€™s people, itâ€™s culture and nature. 

It is a powerful tool to create awareness of cross cultural exchanges and many more that you can achieve through travel photography. 

It is beyond camera settings and filters.

Those are the fundamentals that I will share in my travel photography workshops and coach  potential photography participants who want to learn more on travel and documentary photography.

What is travel photography to you?

Before you sign up for any of my workshops, I encourage you to read, not just reviews on my workshops, but my works as a Travel and Documentary photographer to see whether my expertise and workshops match your requirements:

Before the Butterfly Block was constructed, early HDB residential blocks were largely designed as simple slab blocks and point blocks as the focus then was to build efficiently. With its unique curves and aesthetic faÃ§ade, the Butterfly Block is an effort to create more variety and character in public housing estates through innovative designs.

Paul Fernandez (b. 1940) and his family moved into the Butterfly Block in 1975. He recalled, â€œThere was a circular carriage way, Rumah Bomba (Malay: Fire House) Circus, at the end of the Butterfly Block where the itinerant hawkers would set up their food stalls. The firefighters from Alexandra Fire Station and the expatriates from Gillman Barracks would frequent the food stalls.â€

Exploring the hidden gems of Chinatown and Little India

ğŸ“Chinatown
â€¢Sago Lane / Street of the Dead - In earlier times, funeral parlours lined up this lane.
â€¢People's Park - the "people's shopping centre", the complex is strategically located in one of the most populous areas in Singapore's Central Business District. Also nicknamed as "Streets in the Air"
â€¢Jinrikisha Station - last reminder of the once ubiquitous rickshaw (and yes, it used to be a rickshaw terminal)

ğŸ“Little India
â€¢Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple - one of the oldest Hindu Temple in Singapore (Gopuram/ front tower in photo) 
â€¢Flower Stalls - every street corner of Little India has this
â€¢House of Tan Teng Niah - the last surviving Chinese Villa in Little India
â€¢Sajeev Photography Studio - Most clients are foreign workers whose portaits are sent to their parents back home, to look for their potential brides. (see all those film rolls? can you imagine the numerous love stories that were developed from those!)

Rediscovering Singapore is like getting to know her again for the first time..this time, she looks lovelier than ever as she unfolds stories that were almost forgotten.

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival  is one of the most important religious events for the Taoist community in South East Asia. 
Â 
On the first day of the festival, the devotees gather along the shores of East Coast Park to wait for the arrival of the palanquins and the temple entourage from Leong Nam Temple â€“for the commencement of the receiving ceremony (â€œè¯·æ°´ä»ªå¼Â qing shui yi shiâ€ in Mandarin).Â 
Â 
The ceremony is initiated by a priest who calls upon the Nine Emperor Gods to bestow his presence while devotees pray fervently with a joss stick in their hands.  After the initiation and invitation ceremony, the palanquins carrying the holy artefact (usually an urn) containing the Nine Emperor Gods continue to sway vigorously while the carriers attempt to depart from the coast, and back to the temple.Â

post_caption:
A compilation of the beautiful house of Tan Teng Niah; 
Built in 1900, the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India. Tan Teng Niah was aÂ towkayÂ (Chinese businessman of good standing) Many believe that Tan built the house for his wife and that the inscription referred to her.Â The design of the house were beautifully crafted including the main door inscription made just for his wife. Note of the blossom flowers on the windows. The former house of Tan Teng Niah has eight rooms.

To the Chinese, the house design was auspiciously designed. Each doorway was beautifully decorated with carvings including the twirling wooden stairway of the golden dragons which impressed me most. The carvings were so detailed, precise and elegantly designed. Kudos to the 1900s skillful carpenters. 

The house was restored and conserved in the 1980s for commercial use, and the restoration project was awarded the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention in 1991. It is partially rented out Mr Chandran who had been there for more than 10years. He is a retired police officer whom set up this flower bussiness. I  was fortunate to have him sharing of his experiences and allowing me to take the beautiful interior of the villa.

Family Outing
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

Singapore is known for her diversity in cultures, ethnicities and religions. Due to the travel restrictions and the SingapoRediscover campaign, I have started to explore our neighbourhoods and the history behind these places.

Most locals would know about the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple in Chinatown. This Tang-styled temple is an architectural icon and I like how it contrasts against the modern city skyline in the background. 

Did you know that the street beside it has a sombre history and is known as the "Dead People Street"? Early Chinese immigrants, many of whom had no relatives, lived out their last days in the death houses here. 

Today, this area is a lively and vibrant place. Chinatown Complex is built over part of the street and many elderly folks can be seen playing chess or checkers at the communal spaces. 

Do you know about the history of your neighbourhood? How about taking this opportunity to Rediscover Singapore?

TEOWCHEW MOONCAKES?!
The only surviving traditional Chinese mansion in Singapore, House of Tan Yeok Nee was built in the 1880s and is an interesting Teochew-style residential building with an intricate roof with almost-straight ridges and wooden carvings. Itâ€™s just a small detour from Dhoby Ghaut and Fort Canning Hill!
.
Teochew mooncakes come to my mind when I visit a Teochew-style residential building. Uniquely different from other mooncakes, Teochew Mooncake is made with structurally layered, flaky puff pastry that signifies harmony and deep-fried to give it a golden-brown shade. Each mooncake is filled with lotus seed, mung bean, yam paste and salted duck egg yolk, such as this one from Mitzo.
Â 
More features of mooncakes shot around Singapore at @stb_sg.

Located at corner of Temple Street, at junction with Trengganu Street.

The best thing about cable car rides at @sentosa_island has got to be the stunning views you get to see ğŸ’• Throwback to last weekend's trip to Sentosa when we got the Mastercard 1-for-1 fun pass promo. Other than ten minute each on the Mega Bounce at Mega Adventure for the girls, the fun passes got our whole family on round trips on the Faber and Sentosa cable car lines.
.
The cable car ride is quite a novelty even for us adults and I must say we all so love the views on both lines (an empty Adventure Cove was a little sad to see tho ğŸ˜”). The younger one was a bit nervous initially ğŸ˜… but at the end of the rides they were rather bummed that we couldn't go again.
.
Without the promo, I doubt we would have thought of going for cable car rides. But with the promo it came up to $40 for the four of us - pretty good deal if you ask me ğŸ˜„
.

Most don't think much of a simple Tutu Kueh - little steamed rice-flour cakes filled with single fillings such as peanut, coconut and occasionally chocolate, served over pieces of pandan leafs. As Singapore's hawker culture slowly declines, these little gems are nowadays hard to come by. You find them at traditional shops but rarely are they freshly prepared. 

As a part of Singapore's unique food culture and identity, shops such as Tan's Tutu Kueh are doing their best to keep the hawker culture alive. Known as the OG of Tutu kueh, the family business has been delighting locals with their freshly steamed kuehs since mid 1900s. 

Really enjoy their chocolate and coconut filled Tutu Kuehs and it has become ny go to place for good Tutu Kueh. Heck, I wouldn't even bother trying Tutu Kueh from any other places, they just don't come close. 

Hope that everyone gets to try their famous Tutu Kuehs! They have 2 outlets, located at Havelock Rd and Clementi. Note the timings are different so do check them out before heading down â˜ºï¸

ã€Ang Mo Kio #3 - Fried Riceã€‘
Did you know that it was in the 1970s, that the Chinese name for Ang Mo Kio was changed to â€œå®èŒ‚æ¡¥â€œ which means "Bridge of Expansiveness and Prosperityâ€? Surely such an auspicious name bodes well for the hawkers in this neighbourhood!

China has the earliest record for fried rice from 1,500 years ago. Fried rice is believed to have originated from the Chinese practice of creating a meal with the leftover dishes (and rice) from the  previous meal. Our tradition of not wasting food created a whole new genre of Chinese cuisine.  Some of the usual ingredients for fried rice are rice, scallion, eggs and other small bits of meats & vegetables. 

In Singapore, we have the Chinese version which comes with side dishes like fried egg, hot dog sausage, pork cutlet, etc. Nasi Goreng is the Malay version of fried rice, usually  stir-fried with ikan bilis (anchovies) and tomato sauce. Perhaps because of all the different types of fried rice we get to taste in Singapore, we are known as the â€˜Fried Rice Paradiseâ€™ ?

What kind of ingredients do you  include in your fried rice? Comment below and share with us. See you on Thursday and see where we dabao this delicious packet of fried rice full of â€˜wok heiâ€™. See ya!

post_caption:
Double Rainbow over The Pinnacle @ Duxton HDB. What a beautiful view of the city from my neighbourhood at HDB Kim Tian Green. In this neighbourhood, there are seven blocks of 40 storey tall HDB public housing flats. Every flats have different breathtaking view of the city, ports, towns and nearby islands too. Sometimes, we may get to see rainbow in the morning or in the late afternoon just after the rain. Whenever I saw one in the sky, I will inform my neighbours so that they will not miss seeing the beautiful colours of the rainbow. And I quickly grab my camera and tripod, take the lift up to the highest floor to capture this amazing double rainbows over the city.

HDB Kim Tian Green:

Kim Tian Green have Blk 126A, 126B, 126C, 127A, 127B, 127C & 127D at Kim Tian Road are 40 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 214 units with 78 units of 3-room unit type and 136 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2011 and has a 90 years lease remaining. Kim Tian Green, Blk 126c, Kim Tian Road is located near Tiong Bahru Mrt Station (Ew17).

Kampong â€“ a term to describe traditional villages or urban slum areas in towns and cities. 

In the early days, there used to be many kampongs scattered all over Singapore. However, with development and urbanization, these kampongs have been replaced with modern skyscrapers.

As an urban kid, kampong lifestyle is something that I find it hard to visualize and the only references I have of it are from my grandparentsâ€™ narration of their happy childhood days back in the kampong era.

Upon knowing that there is still the last kampong in Singapore (Kampong Lorong Buangkok), I jumped at the chance to explore it. It was a strange feeling walking through the kampong. Despite being surrounded by the all-so-familiar modern architectures and bustling roads, time seemed to come to a standstill here. Low-rise single-storey houses made of wood with zinc roofs instead of high-rise apartments; lush greeneries instead of dense man-made structures; a peaceful and quiet surrounding instead of the hustle and bustle of the city, this is indeed a whole new world to me!

I took my time to explore and admire the place, soaking up the atmosphere of this lovely location (and at the same time trying very hard to ignore the constant attacks from the bloodsucking mosquito..). This visit has definitely changed my impression of Singapore â€“ there is more to Singapore than meets the eye!!

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival! ğŸŒ•âœ¨ #SeteMilKmEmSingapura â €
â €
One of my favourite things about living in Singapore is celebrating cultural festivals that weren't on our radar before moving to Asia. Today we're celebrating the Mid-Autumn or Moon Festival, which has a history dating back 3000 years! â €
â €
Traditionally it was a time to thank the gods at the end of the autumn harvest, and the festival is celebrated every year on the 15th day of the 8th lunar calendar month. This marks the day the Chinese believed the moon was at its brightest and fullest size, so we're spending the evening looking up to test this theory ğŸ˜‚â €
â €
Paper lanterns in every shape and size can be found decorating many spots in the city, and even though the festival was scaled back this year because of the pandemic, @gardensbythebay still went all out!ğŸ®â €

Really admire Ms Tan Bee Hua, the current owner of Tan's Tutu Kueh. Have been her customer for years and often find myself heading down to her shop just to satisfy my Tutu Kueh cravings. My family is also a fan and Tan's Tutu Kueh is the only place we head to for authentic, pillowy Tutu Kuehs. 

In frame: Ms Tan sieving the rice flour to make it as fine as possible. Running a Tutu Kueh shop alone is tough and labour intensive! You will find Ms Tan at both outlets (Havelock Rd in the early afternoons and then she proceeds to the Clementi outlet at night). Materials have to be prepared in the morning, such as cooking the coconut in gula Melaka and preparing of peanut fillings. All these are very time consuming so I am amazed at how dedicated Ms Tan is. Plus, she mans the shops on her own so you would imagine how many Tutu Kuehs she makes a day, all by hand! 

Really hope that the culture will live on for many more years to come. Glad that nowadays with social media, younger people gaining interest for the hawker culture and local foods. Perhaps in the future, our Singaporean delicacies will be well loved worldwide.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

While my wife had lunch with her friend, I took a chance to try something I've only heard about, Salted and Hung. I went for the "Feed Me" dÃ©gustation menu to have an understanding of Salted and Hung's repertoire. Set aside just under S$200, and be prepared for a culinary ride through Australia, with a dash of Southeast Asia familiarities. 

The range felt playful to me, especially how the very opening bite was an Ebi Panna Cotta... Who the heck starts with dessert? So what's familiar is turned upside down, with this dessert being savoury to the palate. The IPA Sourdough was divine, esp when paired with whipped lard WITH a generous drop of chili oil (you have to try to understand how it plays with you mind!). The other butter was seaweed based, and it was yummy, giving the crunchy bread flavours of the sea. 

Chef Drew and his professional crew did everything so intently, you sense the purpose of the ingredients coming together. More often than not, contemporay fusion food can be a turn off when it's in the chef's mind, but the execution just doesn't mindmeld it to the diner. These guys just did a Spock on me, and I'm pretty damn sure you'll get it too once you give it a go! ğŸ§

post_caption:
Sago Street

Did you know the street received its name because there were numerous sago factories in that area during the 1840s. In the late 19th century, this area became well known for its number of prostitute dens.

Fast forward to the more recent history, this street were occupied by mostly wet and dry markets as well as hawkers. Currently this street is known mainly as a tourist attraction that sell a range of souvenirs and street food, also for the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple which is located along the street.

I did enjoy rediscovering Singapore and finding these hidden photography spots while also trying out street photography which I must admit that Iâ€™m totally bad at it.

Culture and Fashion

It's difficult to not notice women dressed in Kurtis -- the most widely worn women traditional attire in India -- while strolling in Little India. As seen here, they come bright in colours and with floral designs. It brings out elegance and is stylish even in today's times. It's a no wonder that even young Indian ladies would wear them out on the streets today.

1. Elderly lady and her companion outside Tekka Centre.
2. Two ladies exiting from a shophouse onto Campbell Lane.
3. A lady waving for a taxi along Serangoon Road adjacent to Buffalo Road.

[Chinatown Precinct] - â€œPotato Headâ€

Rediscovering is about appreciate the historic value of a place and the finding the best time to shoot it. 

When rediscovering Chinatown, the pre-war shophouses at the junction of Keong Saik Road and Teck Lim Road ( dated 1939) should not be missed.Â  This place has a colorful and rowdy past until 1980. ItÂ  is now occupied by the restaurant-bar Potato Head and now nicknamed as Potato Head. I love the heritage chic and vibe of this area at night. As a photographer, I find it most beautiful in the bluehour of the early morning. This photo was taken during blue hour and just before a heavy rain( which explains the lens flare from the rain drops)

*Taken during the stipulated period. It is challenging during a rainy period. Hope that I made  best of situation.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

7-8 years ago (I think), I came here alone and explored this north part of #singapore with a deep history of #colonial past. Things have remained pretty much the same - there has been no upgrade or redevelopment to this area in #seletar which used to house British military staff. Nonetheless,  the bungalows are one of a kind with double chimneys and even with maid chambers. They are probably beautiful and glorious in the olden days, and though old and derelict and abandoned now, they look as beautiful amidst nature looking to take over the houses. Given their long abandoned state, there is also something eerie about the windows, I can imagine pairs of eyes looking out! Hahaha . I wouldn't dare to explore the insides of the houses, despite my curiosity.  Some of the houses (those with glass panels and are refurbished) are now for commercial use. Within the surroundings, there are also many interesting streets with #british #streetnames such as Hyde Park (the last time I visited, it was barricaded for redevelopment) and Oxford Street, a huge reminder of our colonial past. For now, I can also make pretend that I am travelling in the UK ğŸ˜ğŸ¤£ oh ya, check out the super unique tree in the first picture! Have never seen anything quite like it!

[Little India Precinct] - The Flower Guys of Little India

This is dedicated to the friendly and 
handsome flower garland selling guys of Little India.

Rediscovery is about relooking and presenting the beauty of people in their environment

I am always attracted to the stalls selling colorful flower garlands. Those flower garlands are used for religious purposes during those festivals. Often, those guys are so friendly and always open for a nice photo and chitchat. As I rediscover, I see the beautiful people ( those eyes.. ) and color flower. Cannot help but to capture them in my photos.

Space for Interaction

Beyond the exterior faÃ§ade of being a vibrant place for Singaporeans and tourists to visit, Kampong Gelam is first and foremost a community. Even today, while its early days residents have left, Kampong Gelam continues to instill its energy and vibrance into its visitors, connecting people.

Friends and family, young and old, may find a space in this community that they may relate. This, in particular, can be observed if one were to walk along Haji Lane where friends gather in bars and engage in merrymaking day and night, capturing and creating memories against the colourful shophouses. Not to forget, the relationships forged between the shophouse owners, employers and employees over time. Strangers arrive at Haji Lane and may leave as friends. It's a place to feel alive, to be alive!

Outing with @meixinmacy

The 27 metres long kiln is fired up with wood, creating rivers of fire that engulf the pots in it. The melting ashes then deposit themselves on the pots and reacts with their glazes. This process results in precious one-of-a-kind wares, where each has unique flushes of scorch marks depending of its position in the kiln.

At Thow Kwang, the dragon kiln is fired two to three times a year.

Tour By Hong Thai Travel

Soon after the morning rain, rainbow appears over Jalan Bukit Merah.

HDB Kim Tian 119:

Block 119B, 119C & 119D at Kim Tian Road are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 200 units with 128 units of 4-room unit type and 72 units of 5-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

HDB Membina 118:

Membina 118 have Block 118A, 118B, 118C & 118D at Jalan Membina are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 172 units with 172 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

â€œWe are going to be served Hashbrown.â€ Yes, you heard me right, Chef Bjorn Shen has created, what could possibly, be one of the best hashbrowns that you have ever tasted. New on the menu and to take a dig at the Golden Arches, this version of Homemade Hashbrown ($14) is made from peeled Russet potatoes that have been steamed, grated and seasoned with corn flour and salt before getting a tan in the oven for an hour. If you thought thatâ€™s the end, itâ€™s certainly not as the potato is then fried and topped with sour cream and fresh zaâ€™atar. This might seem like any other hashbrowns that you can get elsewhere but #nothingistooimproper when it comes to Artichoke. The crispy outer shell is just the first layer of amazingness before you reach deeper in to get the warm and starchy potato. The sour cream gives it an uplifting zing that awakens your palate while the spices accentuate the flavour and aroma.
_________________
Artichoke Singapore
Address: 161, Middle Road, Singapore 188978

If you a fan of traditional kopitiam that has not only traditionally brewed authentic coffee aroma but also an old uncle complete in his iconic blue-strip pyjamas, then this time-stood-still coffee shop is for you.  Toasted bread are done over charcoal fire and coffee are done pouring in and out of the brownish-stained coffee bag.  There is even a good olden day timber counter that is no longer used by a cashier, but are stack with traditional biscuits and cookies kept in containers that appear to be used since day one.  If Singapore is serious about preserving its food culture, then this shop has to be gazetted for its intangible cultural heritage that dated back to the 60s and 70s

We always work for a better tomorrow. But when tomorrow comes, instead of enjoying, we again think of a better tomorrow. Letâ€™s have a better today.

What a view of Clementiâ¤ï¸
13 Oct 2020
Clementi is named after Sir Cecil Clementi Smith, the Governor of the Straits Settlement from 1887 to 1893. Part of Clementi used to be swamp land. The other part was made up ofÂ kampungsÂ and villages with squatter-type homes, backyard trades, cottage industries, and farms.

As one of the earliest HDB towns, Clementiâ€™s development took place in the 1970s with plans for the town to be self-sufficient and support an adequate range of facilities and services with job opportunities to meet various social and economic needs.

Clementi has grown from its humble beginnings into a vibrant and popular estate. The town is also known for the many tertiary educational institutions located there, including Ngee Ann Polytechnic, Singapore Polytechnic, and the National University of Singapore.

In the past, I didnâ€™t really thought much when walking past Sago Lane. Did you know during the early 20th century, this lane is famous for its Chinese death houses? 

People in the past were superstitious and believed dying in their own home is considered inauspicious which is why many paid to live their last moments in these houses. 

These houses were banned subsequently in the 1960s. The Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, you see today along Sago Lane was only recently built in the 2000s.

Rediscovering Singapore also brings me back to the area along Sago street, where uncles gather around for a game of chess even during this difficult times (Of course with masks on and social distancing). One of my favourite hobby in the past was to have a game of Chinese chess. It kind of brought me back to the past just by watching them engaging in their mind games. I ended up spending 30 minutes of my time watching that exciting game of chess.

Hardly in our busy work lives, we get to take a walk down these cultural places and enjoy the modern construction as well as the forgotten meaning of these places. Since we couldnâ€™t travel for the time being, why not join me to rediscover Singapore?

I missed Kampong.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a village located in Buangkok in Hougang, Singapore. Built in 1956, it is the last surviving kampong located on Singapore Island.

Decide to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks there and one even invited me to their home for a chat.

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my kampong childhood, living in my grandfather's house in Chua Chu Kang.

The kids here run freely and the  folks here are always obliging for a chat and phototaking, which is true in the kampong spirit.

You can see herbs, mango trees and even coca plant.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone to experience kampong lifestyle.

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

The announcement of the winners of the Design For Deities competition will be delayed by a couple of weeks. Our day jobs have been keeping us busy... our apologies! 

In the meantime, here's sharing another shortlisted entry. 

This is from product designer Jason Fok, originally from Mauritius, now based in Singapore. (www.fokchiseng.com)

In his design, the Monkey God is posable and made of simple geometric shapes. Unlike the traditional effigies, his design uses colour sparingly. The traditional motifs of dragons and armour is reinterpreted with elegance - peach-shaped armour plates and whimsical clouds on the base. The movable parts encourage you to tinker with it constantly, a departure from the reverence and distance that traditional effigies exert on worshippers. 

A few hundred people have voted in the competition so far. Pls join them to support our amazing designers by voting via the link in bio!

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

To me it's all about the broth, and this one is not bad, though I still prefer the mega prawn noodles at Zion Road Food Centre where the broth has more kick.

Pulau Ubin is one of the 64 islands/islets that make up Singapore and a welcome tropical getaway if you want to escape the city for a day. The once bustling island used to be explored for its granite - Pulau Ubin actually means "Granite Island" in Malay - but nowadays the abandoned quarries have turned into lakes and less than 50 people live there.â €
â €
Hiking, biking, swimming, kayaking (and of course taking pictures ğŸ˜‚), Pulau Ubin has lots to offer just a 10 minute boat ride away. There are also bike rentals, little shops and restaurants owned by the locals - probably the last witnesses of the Singaporean way of life prior to the country's fast modernisation.â €
â €

Central Fire Station
â 
The Central Fire Station (CFS), also known as the Hill Street Fire Station, is Singaporeâ€™s oldest surviving fire station. Completed in 1909, the distinctive red-and-white brick building was gazetted as a national monument by the Preservation of Monuments Board in recognition of its significance in Singaporeâ€™s history. The Singapore Civil Defence force subsequently embarked on conservation and reconstruction work, including building the Heritage Gallery to commemorate the contributions and rich history of the local fire service and its firemen. The gallery is located in the oldest part of the station, and features photographs of major fires, old firefighting equipment and uniforms, interactive displays, and audio-visual presentations to engage the public. Its highlights include a 19th-century fire engine, and the 30-metre lookout tower that visitors can climb up.â 
.â

Not sure if you notice; because of the fengshui, peranakan houses are designed symmetrically with entrance located in the centre flanked by windows on the both sides. Itâ€™s also common to have Chinese inscribed signboard hung above the main door as well as ventilation openings carved in wood with symbolic decorations.

On Koon Seng Rd, Joo Chiat, you can find the bat-shaped ventilations which actually symbolize Good Luck. Here is something Iâ€™m very sure you didnâ€™t notice until now; swipe to see a close-up, spot the bat-shaped ventilations and compare it with the logo of @stb_sg ğŸ˜‰
