SingapoRediscovers 3 Oct 2020

It's saturday fever.  Nobody in the street in early morning.  A rare and quiet scene around Chinatown. A contrast between the used to be buzzling town filled with festive moods and lifestyle comparing to the diminishing kampong village where I grew up from.

Ironically, this Sago street used to be death houses and today a temple is built here.

Covid-19 may have slowed down our lifestyle, our economy and taking away many lives.  While what were lost, there are always new opportunities, new beginnings and new discovery.

To me, Singapore rediscovers is to revisit some of my growing up fond memories places and/or find new created memories and values through every visits.

Walking down the memory street, checking out what we have been missing during those vibrant good days, refresh our childhood memories, spending more time with family, revisit Singapore and it's diverse culture and foods.  Without covid-19, we may be complacent, and always think that the other part of the pasture are greener.  It is this covid-19 that set our mindset to another new level of critical thinking, to unlearn, learn and relearn. To appreciate and be thankful that we are borned in Singapore, with the great contribution from our fore fathers especially from our founding father Mr Lee Kuan Yew.

Will Singapore continue to be a vibrant first world country? It's a test on #SGUnited.

Delightful chaos and beautiful disarray. That is usually the state of the studio after a full day of workshops.
.
TBH, preparing for and cleaning up after classes take up a lot of time and frankly aren't much fun at all. And these are just some of many invisible behind-the-scenes things we do to create the art experience we want to deliver for every single guest who visit the studio. 
.
But the hard work all pays off when we see the galore of works that our workshop participants create after every session. Each piece different and always inspiring in one way or another. And if even when only one person leaves the studio having a renewed perspective towards art, we do a little dance in our heart.ğŸ’ƒ
.
So when you're feeling tired like we do today, take a moment to look for that delight in chaos and beauty in disarray, and then find new strength to keep going. For us, we wake up grateful every day to be able to call this our career, our passion and our mission ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€ğŸ¨ Here's to another brand new day. Fighting!
.

For this weekend, we decided to visit Canopy Park at @jewelchangiairport and the Walking Net inside the park! We had always wanted to visit #CanopyPark but had been putting it off thinking that it would be rather crowded since it was fairly new and the prices to the attractions inside are really quite steep. Well, now till end August there's a 55% off for the attractions at Canopy Park and that finally got us there ğŸ˜†
.
Some of the attraction tickets, including our Walking Net tics, include Canopy Park entrance fees and essentially we paid slightly over $20 for our family of four. I had thought my girls would be fine with the Walking Net given that they were fearless at Airzone (the net playgound at City Square Mall), but they were rather spooked by the height (you can see all the way down to the mall) and they said a lot harder to walk on compared to Airzone. I quite agree with them; we were all drenched in sweat by the time we made our way to the end of the net. But that said, we got the hang of it - the trick is to side step - and soon we all found the net to be quite enjoyable to walk around and sit on ğŸ˜†
.
It wasn't very crowded when we were there on Saturday morning - only a little crowded with children at the Foggy Bowls. We were expecting more people given that Jewel just started a promo where you can redeem Canopy Park entry for 2 pax with one receipt of any amount spent at Jewel (1st 500 redemptions). The girls had a field day at the Discovery Slides (only 2 slides out of 4 operating btw) and they didn't even have to queue despite a capacity limit of 5 at any one time at Discovery Slides.
.
We're thinking of the Bouncing Nets (bookings for these seem to have sold out fast!) and Canopy Bridge next. Anyone know if these two attractions are good? ğŸ˜Š
.

This building along #ToaPayoh Lorong Two is the headquarters of Singapore Federation of Chinese Clan Associations (SFCCA) since 1997. 

Prior to that, this premises used to belong to Heng A Khe Bong #School, a primary school that started in 1973 but traced its roots to two separate institutions - Heng A School (founded in 1918) and Khe Bong School (in 1920).

The two schools came together and stayed together before it closed down in 1993.

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Boardâ€™s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

Hike in the city at Fort Canning.

Since weâ€™re encouraged to be local tourists, we decided on a hike at Fort Canning Park. ğŸ’¡Hereâ€™s a tip for parents, print the map ğŸ—º from NParks and make your kids the â€œtour guideâ€, with Jubilee Park as the last stop so theyâ€™ll press on for the PLAY incentive!
 
There are nine historical gardens and we explored half of them yesterday. We started at The Foothills after lunch at Clarke Quay and made our way up the Raffles Garden where we were greeted by the Fort Canning Lighthouse on top of Fort Canning Hill. Next was the Instagram worthy Sang Nila Utama Garden ğŸŒºwith Javanese split gates, recreated to resemble the 14th century royal palace gardens. We spent some time at the Artisanâ€™s Garden which featured an archaeological dig exhibition site along with displayed artefacts that were unearthed since the 1980s. We didnâ€™t manage to cover all 9 gardens and itâ€™s a pity The BattleBox tour is now closed due to COVID-19 but Iâ€™m sure weâ€™ll be back again.

To conclude our day of adventure- play time at Jubilee Park which is across Liang Court. The climbing nets and long slide are now closed but thankfully the swings, see-saw, log scramble and slides at the toddler area kept the young and young at heart very happy! 

Fort Canning is easily accessible by train from Fort Canning and Clarke Quay MRT stations. Donâ€™t forget to put on comfortable walking shoes, slap on sunscreen, mosquito repellant and go armed with a sense of adventure where youâ€™ll definitely be rewarded for a journey back in time experience!

We finally explored a beautiful oasis so close to our home here in Singapore: the Sembawang Hot Springs. We rode our bikes and found great bike park facilities, restrooms and surprisingly a cafe that rents & sells buckets for the hot springs. The pools are nestled in regenerated natural bush and the only sign of the busy neighbourhood is the occasional helicopter overhead.  The surprise and delight of the â€˜egg cookingâ€™ station was surpassed by our genuine surprise at how hot the water is in the foot bath spring pool. Weâ€™ll definitely be back (with a bucket).

Happy 1st Birthday, Jewel @ Changj Airport
.
Officially opened on October 18th, 2019. Jewel receives about 300,000 visitors a day. In October 2019, six months after its soft opening, it had already welcomed 50 million visitors, exceeding its initial target for the whole of the first year. 
In November 2019, Jewel Changi Airport was awarded the Special Jury Award at the year'sÂ MapicÂ Awards, which recognises excellence, innovation and creativity in the global retail real estate industry. Jewel Changi Airport had initially submitted entries in two categories - Best Leisure Concept and Best Shopping Mall - but the panel, comprising top retail real estate experts, gave it the Special Jury Award, which goes to the jury's favourite project among all the entries.

The Changi Jurassic Mile â€“ a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species â€“ is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

#deskerroad is located within the Rochore planning area in the Central Region of Singapore.1 This stretch of road was built after the completion of land reclamation works in the old Kampong Kapor area.2 It is laid out in an orthogonal (at right angles) manner between two main roads â€“ Serangoon Road and Jalan Besar.3 It was named after Andre Filipe Desker, a former resident of the area and butchery owner in the 1860s.4 

Once notoriously known as a â€œred-light areaâ€,5 Desker Road still retains its old-world charm with its rows of conserved terrace shophouses lining some parts of the road.6 In addition, it is the site where 88 flats under the public housing programme were built by the Housing and Development Board (HDB) in 1982.7 The prevailing vibrant landscape of Desker Road is linked to other commercial developments such as condominiums, restaurants, shopping and hotels, located within the areas around Jalan Besar, reflecting the current needs of the population it now serves.

ã€Sengkang #1 â€“ Char Siew Noodleã€‘
Situated at the North-Eastern part of Singapore, Sengkang was once occupied by fishing villages, rubber and pepper plantations. During the mid-20th century, this area was known as â€œKangkarâ€ which literally means â€œFoot of Harbourâ€.

Although with younger generations residing at this district, the love of local hawker food remains identical to any other part of Singapore. Sengkang has a wide array of hawker fare and even had their very first vending machines cafeÌ for all the dabao-food lovers.

To kick-start our feature on Sengkang, we picked a traditional staple menu in most hawker centres â€“ Char Siew Noodle.
 
A perfect serving of Char Siew Noodle contains egg noodles cooked al dente, tossed in flavoured sauce and topped with slices of yummy, slightly charred roast pork and leafy vegetables. Simple but satisfying!

Where is your favourite Char Siew Noodle stall? Comment below to tell us where to find this traditional dish. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.

[Kovan/Buangkok Precinct] Last Kampong in Singapore and amongst us

Rediscovery is about exploration and searching for new perspective to present it.

Do you know we still have kampong in Singapore?Â 

Do you know that the last kampong is right next to our public housing estate?

We have come a long way for housing in Singapore. It is great to rediscover the old kampong days of Singapore face to face. You can get to see those old road signage with 4 digit postal code ( Photo 1). It is amazing to find a real kampong amongst the green (photo2) It also  always surprised me that it is right next to our public housing estate ( Photo 3) . It is worth a visit before it is gone.

ã€Ang Mo Kio #2 - Wanton Meeã€‘
Feeling artsy? Then you really have to make a trip to the hawker centre at block 724. Beside the vibrantly-painted walkways and stone tables, check out the wall murals at the side of some of the iconic buildings in AMK-hood that have been around since the 80s.

Since we have covered the Singapore-style Wanton Mee two years ago, it's time we work on the next most popular style - Pontian Wanton Mee. This wanton mee chain is almost everywhere in Singapore now. This version of Pontian-style wanton mee comes with a savoury black sauce served with a fried dumpling. 

#dabaogram decided to give Pontian Wanton Mee a more refreshing look. We torched the BBQ pork, re-arranged the noodles, baked the leaves of the vegetables to give them a more crispy texture and topped our creation with some spring onions and flowers. Viola!

We would like to thank Pontian Wanton Mee for bringing these yummy bowls of noodles from across the Causeway. It means so much to us now especially when we are not able to travel, not even Johor Bahru. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own â€˜dabaogramâ€™ at home. 

Singapore, fried rice paradise? See ya next week!

Yay we finally went to the Artscience Museum! In the Future World:
Where Art Meets Science exhibition, there were lots of fun for us as we explored the interactive installations. Some of them were breathtaking and lots were simply very cute!!!! 

We highly recommend a visit there because it's just too fun! There's proper crowd control and you will be given a pair of gloves since there are lots of interactive screens. Sanitisers are available everywhere for the younger ones who can't keep their gloves on.

A Living Space

Strolling along the streets of Kampong Gelam, one may find many shophouses providing all sorts of services such as hairstyling, food and drinks and souvenirs; there are also shophouses selling colourful Turkish lamps, mats, or aromatic perfumes and fragrances. What caught my eye on this particular trip, however, were the Turkish lamps that offered a dazzling array of colours -- it fitted perfectly in this district of vibrant walls and colourful shophouses.

For the employers and employees of the various shophouses, Kampong Gelam is not just a place for recreation. It's also a place of livelihood. It's a place where they spend most of their waking hours living. As seen here, this at times includes temporarily transforming these public spaces into their personal living space -- a space for prayer. It's a space to feel alive and to be alive.

For enlarged version, see InstaStory.

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Boardâ€™s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

Just. can't. ignore. those. curves. snaking. ğŸ¤­

<364> â€œWalking Into A Time Tunnel" 

This is a time tunnel. Try it, if you do not believe me.

After many years, I once again set foot on this underground walkway from Marine Parade town center to East Coast Park this morning. Before I got out of the tunnel, many memories from my youthful years were erupting. 

Do you remember yourself going to the East Coast Park with your friends together to ride bicycles, barbecue food, sing songs, watch the sea and chat â€˜till dawn? Do you also remember the friend who was always sticking with you? And do you remember how you yearned to be with someone you like, while looking at your friends who had found someone they loved with envy? Those were the precious memories of youth!

If you would like to relive those memories, I suggest that you enter this time tunnel!

Bukit Brown Cemetery

Estimated to house 100,000 tombs in a vast land size of about 0.86 square kilometers, Bukit Brown Cemetery has been abandoned since its closure in 1973. It was opened in 1922 by the Municipal Council (Municipal Council oversaw the supplies of water, electricity, gas, maintenance of roads, lighting and other administrative things in Singapore before 1965).

The grandest and largest tomb site in Bukit Brown Cemetery lies on its tallest hill and covers an area of  600 square meters, roughly the size of ten, 3- bedroom HDB flats (public housing apartments). 

Read Here For More Information : https://remembersingapore.org/bukit-brown-cemetery/

Have always enjoyed eating chwee kueh but have not really had one that was memorable. Recently I kept seeing posts about an elderly uncle who sells chwee kueh at Taman Jurong Food Center. His chwee kuehs are very popular amongst those living around the area. Uncle actually makes the chwee kueh daily. Wanted to visit to support and also try out the famed chwee kuehs for myself. A good way to #supportlocal ğŸ˜‚ note that his shop doesn't exactly have a name but the sign says æ°´ç²¿. Shop number #02-67!

Glad to say that the chwee kuehs were tasty! Enjoyed the smooth texture of the rice cakes that had a delicate chewy texture. The chye poh were for me both savoury yet sweet and surprisingly they were not too oily. Think the chilli which was on the sweeter side also went well with the kuehs. In all, it isn't something that will blow your mind but you can definitely taste the difference in quality as compared to other chwee kuehs. The contrasting savoury and sweetness in the chye poh gives it an edge over other versions too. 

Uncle manages the store by himself so waiting time could get long but it's worth the wait! His shop closes at 1.30pm daily so have to go early!

â€œThe only surviving traditional Chinese mansion in Singapore, House of Tan Yeok Nee, was built in the 1880s and is an interesting Teochew-style residential building with an intricate roof with almost-straight ridges and wooden carvings. Itâ€™s just a small detour from Dhoby Ghaut and Fort Canning Hill! 

Teochew mooncakes come to my mind when I visit this Teochew private residence. Uniquely different from the other mooncakes, Teochew mooncakes are made with structurally layered, flaky puff pastry that signifies harmony and deep-fried to give it a golden-brown shade. Each mooncake is filled with lotus seed, mung bean, yam paste and salted duck egg yolk, such as this one from @mitzosg.â€

Captured by @stormscape as part of #SingapoRediscovers â€“ tell us if youâ€™ve ever tried a Teochew mooncake in the comments below.

Took some time this week to visit the Little India precinct a.k.a. Tekka. As I strolled around, I bumped into this colorful house, which is known as the Former House of Tan Teng Niah. This colorful house is the last surviving Chinese Villa in the area, and the story inspires me a lot because it displayed how the small Chinese industries operated alongside the Indian cattle and rattan trade.

I then walked around the area a little bit more and never got bored of it. It always surprised me. For instance, I found a lot of beautiful murals such as the Cattleland 2, which shows several cows interacting with each other in different activities and created that sense of community.

"Pretty enjoyable exploration!", I must say. A place worth visit to everyone who wants to learn about what it means to have culture strongly amplified through the sense of diversity and belonging.

First timer at the hotspring. Heard its about 40 degrees at the foot dipping area, but I feel its more than that, as the hotspring source is already at 70 degrees. 

Most people dare not put their feet in entirely, because it really does feel like putting your foot in boiling water. I was hovering too initially, but got tired and decided to just plonk my feet in. Turned out it actually feels good. Sure does promote blood circulation because my feet became red like lobster after 30s of dipping. 

Take a container and some eggs along too to make some onsen eggs! ğŸ¥šğŸ¥šğŸ¥š

<353> â€œProbably one of the liveliest places in the heartland of Singaporeâ€

This is a high-ceiling sheltered alley that is lined with a large diversity of small shops that provide every daily need and service you can imagine at the most affordable prices. 

Its most unique feature is the temporary stalls that are set up outside the shops where the sellers promote all sorts of interesting things of the season. 

The place is always bursting at seams in the weekends from morning to the evening. Lured by its local vibes, even on a weekday, there is no short of human traffic.

I would confidently say that it is probably one of the liveliest shopping arcades in the heartland of Singapore. If you drop by, let me show you around.

William

Singaporeâ€™s oldest Hindu temple was built in 1827 by immigrants from the Nagapatnam and Cuddalore districts of South India. The Sri Mariamman Temple is dedicated to Goddess Mariamman, known for her power in curing epidemic illnesses and diseases

During the colonial times, it served as a refuge for new immigrants, hosted community activities and acted as the Registry of Marriages for Hindus when it was the only authorised venue to solemnise Hindu marriages

Trishaw Uncle (ä¸‰è½®è½¦å¤§å”) a tribute to all trishaw riders, for providing transport services rain or shine, from the time before cars, buses and trains back in the olden days.
In Singapore, children are taught to address elders as â€œUnclesâ€ and â€œAuntiesâ€ as a form of respect. â€œTrishaw Uncleâ€ is a term of endearment for the trishaw riders who formed the early backbone of Singaporeâ€™s labour force, using their manual strength to get people to places.

During my younger days I had my trishaw expedition through the colourful, quaint and bustling streets of Singapore, from Chinatown to Little India, experienced the nostalgic memories and dynamic aspirations of our country in a very different way.

Stones Stacking
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1998, the Ministry of Defence (Mindef) acquired the land containing the spring for the expansion of the nearby Sembawang Air Base, leaving F&N with less than 4 hectares (10 acres) of land. Its water-bottling plant survived until the early 1990s however. In January 2002, locals' interest to the hot spring, which had caught the attention of Singaporeans after the surrounding land had been cleared to begin the RSAF air base extension. Sembawang community leaders gathered signatures to petition Mindef, which was going to fence off the area, to preserve & develop the hot spring for the general public. Mindef gave the green light to the appeals & opened a small side gate pavement for the public to access the spring.

During that same year, a series of scalding cases, including an incident in which a senior citizen diabetic lost six toes to gangrene after soaking in the hot spring, prompted the Singapore General Hospital to warn that people with nerve disorders or diseases affecting blood circulation should be cautious to hot mineral springs. As a result of some negative rumors and hearsay, and the RSAF redevelopment, public interest began to wane & the number of visitors dwindled.

With overseas travel off limits for a while to come, CNA journalists Matthew Mohan and Gaya Chandramohan set off on a marathon walk around Singapore to see how appealing their home really is.

Had an awesome morning at @nestopia_sg at @sentosa_island today! The girls had a ball of a time climbing nets, crossing bridges and sliding down slides (one's pretty fast and steep, they say!). Being outdoors at 10am was rather hot though, especially with face masks on ğŸ˜… But they lasted for the hour we were booked for!
.
Honestly, I wasn't sure I'd visit Nestopia when I first heard about it as you have to pay entrance fees ($9-10/hr) - Singapore has loads of free outdoor playgrounds after all ğŸ˜†. We decided to visit after redeeming the free NDP Sentosa tokens (go redeem yours if you haven't!) which covered entry for two kids (one adult can enter free with a kid). When we got there, I was pretty impressed by the playground structure. It looked about two stories high which made it really exciting for the kids. And thereâ€™s something about playing at a playground with the beach in the background - felt like we were on holiday somewhere! The kids enjoyed themselves so much they wanted to return another time - I said okay, if there is promo on the entrance fees ğŸ˜‹
.
It wasn't crowded the Tuesday school holiday morning we were there with only around 8 kids. Apparently late afternoon weekends are pretty popular though. There's a capacity limit of 15 kids now, so do call ahead to book a slot if you're planning to visit ğŸ˜Š
.

#beautiful #temple of the #earth #god sitting with a moat. It was raining heavily, but it is a picture of #tranquility in the raging rain. It feels like overseas, and I wish I have more time to walk about and explore rather than the 15 mins or so I visit the island every 10 years or so. 

The middle aged couple living there tending to the temple must be feeling quite isolated from life on the mainland. The uncle I spoke to says it needs getting used to. But then I was also thinking, you get a peaceful life and an island to yourselves, isnt that great? Maybe in freedom, there is also a responsibility (manning the temple), and maybe isolation and peaceful life isn't such a great thing?

We were at @rwsentosa USS last Friday. I was surprised that Sushi had so much fun and was so brave in trying out the rides! He requested to go again, and refused to get off the 2nd round ğŸ˜…#thingsmomwoulddoforkids 
He came home and told everyone that he took the rollercoaster and he protected mama because mama was screaming. Such a sweet darling! 
I am just glad to have spent some quality time with him, even if it meant messy hair, sweaty face, getting blisters on my feet, having heat rash and running around to catch the meet n greet despite my burning achilles, it is ALL WORTH IT to see how much he enjoyed himself. â¤ï¸

House of Tan Teng Niah

This vividly colorful house is located at Little India and was constructed in 1900 by a local businessman named Tan Teng Niah. It underwent a full restoration during the 1980s to what people see today. This vibrant and beautiful building has stood the test of time, representing hope and resilience. 

Conservational buildings, like the House of Tan Teng Niah, are being preserved to keep a balance between the modern and traditional structures. These buildings are valued because of their history and their significant impact to which I believe more people, not only locals but tourists too, should rediscover and learn more about. The intrinsic and unique design of these buildings will surely captivate your eyes.

If you are there, and have no reserved the pork satays, donâ€™t worry, you can always go for the chicken satay, and THEY ARE REALLY GOOD! Oh... the pineapple satay sauce... man... old school taste... 

Had carbonara prepared by Chef L, and that small portion is actually a lot. 

Ben managed to get me some pork satay which some customers let go, and these pork satay is different from the traditional ones we have... 
Iâ€™m not going to share more, you have to try it yourself! 

Love the quiet environment which allows me to do some of my work. If itâ€™s not of the rain, I would have stay a little longer.

#SingapoRediscovers journey sans the vouchers checking out the historical constitutional documents and oil paintings of Singapore.

I saw the treaty letter in 1819, the surrender document, the proclamation of merger with federation of Malaya, the draft letter to separate and our proclamation of independence. The latter gave me the damn chills.

At the Siapa Namu Kamu exhibition, especially love the National Language Class painting and how it defined the sign of the times when nationalism was strong and there was a collective desire among our parents and grandparents to forge a national identity. #nationalgallery #singapoliday #art #culture #museum #singaporediscovers #singapoliday

Rediscovering Joo Chiat/Katong and Kampong Gelam

ğŸ“Joo Chiat / Katong
â€¢Former Queen's Theatre - one of the main entertainment places in Geylang from 1930 to 1982
â€¢Mindanao Gum Heritage Tree (Rainbow Tree) - has distinctive peeling bark with multi-coloured streaks. Why are there so many colours? This is because the patches of outer bark are shed at different times, showing the bright-green inner bark which matures to give blue, purple, orange and then maroon tones.
â€¢Archeological Dig for Fort Tanjong Katong - remnants of Fort Tanjong Katong which stood from 1879 to 1901, was one of the oldest military forts built by the former British colonial  government of Singapore

ğŸ“Kampong Gelam
â€¢Masjid Sultan (Golden Mosque)- focal point for Singaporeâ€™s Muslim community. The onion-shaped dome base is decorated with glass bottle ends, donated by lower-income Muslims during its construction so that all Muslims, not just the rich, could contribute.
â€¢Streetside Barber - the last of Singapore's streetside barber shop ($6.00 only! open everyday except Wed and Sun)

Isn't it amazing that there's a piece of history in almost all corners of Singapore? Behind the industrialization and development the country is going through, may the memories of yesteryears be kept alive for the next generations to see.

Another spot at #ToaPayoh Central that has transformed over the years.

The spot where the local @courtssg outlet occupied used to be the post office which in front of it stood a sculpture of a man lifting a woman, although I am quite sure the post office was not the first occupant of the old building.

The two housing blocks at the back of the picture used to be two of four accommodated the athletes competing in the 1973 SEAP Games.

Lastly, the two-storey building on the right of the picture used to house the local outlet of the now-defunct Emporium (è‹±ä¿è‰¯) departmental store.

2020 has been an absolute rollercoaster of a year, as the world recovers from a depression â€” both literally and figuratively. This only makes festive occasions all the more precious, as we realise who the most important people in our lives are: family.

Being the only immediate kin I have, my mother has been the person I've spent the most time with over the last few years. This year has made that the case even more so, due to us being responsible people and staying home almost 24/7.

Taking the time to head out to Chinatown was a welcome break from the routine of staying home, made even more special by her agreeing to be photographed â€” trust me, this is especially rare.

As such, I'll be spending this Mid-Autumn Festival 2020 with the most important person in my life, as she rounds out her last few decades here with me.

I did not know we had such amazing hiking trails within Singapore till few of my friends(Shuchi Kapoor  Seema Balani) decided to explore the place . It was love at first sight when I looked at the pics and I decided that it was my next destination in Singapore to explore.
 MacRitchie reservoir is a place to enjoy tranquility if walking above a lush green foliage.I bumped into monkeys, monitor lizard and squirrels .
Macritchie can be termed Singaporean cousin of famous Cloud forest trail in Laos.
A must visit place says Ballo  either early in morning or evening ( before sunset) with your friends and family .

post_caption:
Tee Seng Store is one of Singaporeâ€™s oldest provision stores. Located in a quiet private housing estate, this modest shop has been operated by Mr Ang Lu Heng since 1955.
.
Provision shops â€“ known colloquially as mini-marts, mama shops, or zhap hueh diam (æ‚è´§åº—) â€“ are witnesses to our memories, both personal and shared. Many of us often take these provision shops for granted, only remembering how important they are when we need an ice-cold drink, the occasional bottle of soya sauce, or that essential packet of coconut milk for our curries.
.
Many of us also grew up with the uncles and aunties who ran the provision shops â€“ just like Mr Ang here. The octogenarian wakes up at 5am daily to practice qigong before opening his store at 8am like clockwork. Over the years, Mr Ang has built up a small but loyal following of customers, whose names and orders he knows by heart. This is the familiarity that modern supermarket chains and convenience stores cannot give. Because what the humble provision shop lacks in newfangled products, it more than makes up for in faithfulness and a wealth of memories.
.
Stepping into Tee Seng Store was like taking a trip down memory lane. Mr Ang once used a Milkmaid tin that dangled from the ceiling to store cash. Now, he uses a cash register. I was fortunate to have Mr Angâ€™s permission to take pictures of his store while he worked. These pictures are precious reminders of days gone by.
.
Rediscovering Singapore does not have to be anything grand. To me, it is about revisiting these living artefacts of Singaporeâ€™s past and getting reacquainted with these simple but deeply cherished memories of growing up.
.

You want to get started with night photography but not to spend that long 4 hours. 

I get it !

So I came up with a 2 hours workshop

What weâ€™ll do... 

Iâ€™ll coach you the basic elements of night photography, providing you with tips and techniques of low light and long exposure photography. 

We will be working on camera settings to create different effects to capture fascinating images as the day changes from twilight hour into the night. 

What youâ€™ll get...

At the end of the workshop, you will acquire the knowledge to capture light trails, to create the effect of light burst and silky waters, creating stunning colour tones to your night images as well as capturing modern and historical architecture illuminated with colourful lights that adorned the cityscape.

No filter required!

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

Where weâ€™ll be...

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

What others said....

Donâ€™t just hear this from me. 

Swipe to your left to read what participant has to say about this workshop.

All that for $120 per person.

And thatâ€™s not the end of us...

I keep the communication channel open for all my workshopsâ€™ past and present participants. 

Participants still text or email me from time to time, checking in on unclear camera setups, asking for opinions and reviews of their work. 

Book your spot through info@carolinepang.com

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
é¾å—æ®¿ä¹çš‡å¤§äºŒå¸çˆ·åƒç§‹
ä¹æœˆåˆğŸ—“ğŸ™ğŸ™ğŸ™

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

ã€Ang Mo Kio #4 - Ngoh Hiangã€‘
With Singaporeans' love of crispy flavourful fried food items, no wonder Ngoh Hiang is such a popular dish here! You can find it in almost every hawker centre in Singapore. Tell us about YOUR favourite neighbourhood Ngoh Hiang stall!

Did you have a hard time figuring out how we piled up the vermicelli? Here is what we did: First, we stacked some fish cakes to make a tower and covered the entire structure with vermicelli. We then balanced the all-time-favourite crispy prawn cracker on the tower and gingerly arranged all the other ingredients on top. Reminds us of those elegant ladies' hats at the Kentucky Derby races! To add some greens to the dish, we added some leaves from our backyard. If you watched the video, you would see the pink sweet sauce make a special appearance towards the end.

We would like to thank S11 Coffee Shop Jin Long Wu Xiang stall near Cheng Sa Market for preparing and serving such wide variety of Ngoh Hiang items. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own â€˜dabaogramâ€™ at home. 

We hope youâ€™ve enjoyed our tour in Ang Mo Kio so far, take part in our IG Story poll to share with us which is your favourite dish! 

Next stop, Seng Kang! See you soon!

[Kampong Gelam Precinct] - Sultan Mosque Re-discovered

Rediscovery is about understand the historical significant of the place  and the finding suitable lighting moments to capture it so that there is clear message to communicate.

Previously, I have taken photo of Sultan Mosque in different lighting conditions. Decide to re-discoverÂ  the iconic Sultan Mosque in the late morning when the dome of the mosque is brightly reflected with the glory of sunâ€™s ray together with a deep blue sky. A hope to capture a shot that remind us that the future ahead will be brighter for Singapore - we need to stay strong together

This place used to be crowded with tourists and locals. Since the Covid19 pandemic, you see much fewer crowds, and thus opportunity for a cleaner shot without distracting elements. This is the best chance to re-discover the place again before the crowd returns ;)Â Â

22 on 22. Did you know that this large halo that appeared around the sun and seen by many in Singapore at around noon today (22 Sep) is what scientists call a â€œ22-degree haloâ€? (Because the ring has a radius of approximately 22 degrees around the sun.) So yup, 22 on 22ğŸ‘½
.
What causes this phenomenon? Millions of tiny ice crystals in cirrus clouds that refract and reflect light in just the right orientation and position with respect to your eye for the halo to be visible.
.
Stay safe, and look up, people. You wonâ€™t find rainbows on the ground.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
@ Leong Nam Temple 
é¾å—æ®¿ä¹çš‡å¤§äºŒå¸çˆ·åœ£è¯ 
Rain or shine...devotees come in drove to offer prayers to the Nine Emperor Gods.
The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. Today, the younger generations have taken an interest in the festival, with many youths taking part in the processions. Involving the younger generations allows us to continue this intangible cultural heritage for many generations to come.

<359> â€œHave You Seen Any Crocodile?â€ 

Daunted by the inaccessibility of public transport and the fear of mosquito bites in a swampy forest, I had avoided visiting Sungei Buloh Wetland for a long time. 

Today, I was delighted to discover a new entrance to the wetland at Kranji Reservoir. And it was a pleasure to walk above the mudflat by crossing a suspension bridge and a coastal boardwalk. Thankfully, too, there were no mosquitoes today! Rather, there were butterflies and birds.

A passer-by asked me, looking disappointed, â€œI see many signboards cautioning about crocodiles. But I spotted none so far. Had you seen a crocodile?â€

Bemused by his question, I shook my head and let out a laugh. 

William

Buddha Relic Tooth Temple

"Rediscover and appreciating one of the hidden beauty and gem of Singapore. Such a beautiful and magnificent structure"

This Tang-styled Chinese Buddhist temple is located in the historic district of Chinatown, Singapore. It has richly designed interiors and comprehensive exhibits on Buddhist art and history which tell stories of culture over thousands of years old. The buildingâ€™s design was inspired by the Buddhist Mandala, a symbol of Buddhist culture that represents the universe.

Singapore as we all know is a place rich in culture with people still embracing the principles and beliefs passed to them through generations. Prayer is an integral part of the their culture - regardless of what religion you are in. Temples are found all over Singapore and their distinct beauty shines through despite being surrounded by modern buildings. It is a place of worship and where people spend time with their loved ones such as offering incense and attend meditations. Visiting these temples will help you to understand and experience the culture and beliefs of the people In Singapore.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] The Red House of Katong.

Rediscovery is about exploring angles and lighting of presenting the subjects. I was not very happy with shooting with the road divider( photo3)

I have visited this location a few times. Finally, I found the right lighting and angle (photo 1 and 2) to capture this iconic building. 

The Red House Bakery is a popular reference to the iconic confectionery shop, Katong Bakery & Confectionery. It was a popular breakfast place amongst Singaporeans living in the eastern part of Singapore, especially for its signature cakes and curry puffs. It was established in 1925 but closed on 23 March 2003 after the shophouse where it was occupying was deemed as unsafe. It has since reinvented itself. Currently, it houses a bakery cafe - Micro Bakery & Kitchen Red House

â€œCantonese mooncakes are most commonly seen in Singapore. The golden brown pastry is filled with lotus paste and an optional salted duck egg, glazed with egg yolks before baking. Apart from lotus paste, the less common red date paste is also used as Cantonese mooncake filling. The red date paste gives it a dark red tone with slight fruity and citrus taste.

(2/3) A different color for a different vibe.

â€œEver seen a mooncake as large as this? Originating from the largest dialect group in Singapore, the Hokkien mooncake is also known as the Scholar Cake, distributed to those who sat for the Imperial examinations in ancient China.

Each Hokkien mooncake is made of candied winter melon, tangerine peel, melon and sesame seeds, sugar, and lard. I chose the Hokkien mooncake from the 89-year-old Tan Hock Seng Shop at Telok Ayer and was greeted by a warm and cheery old lady. She asked if I was getting it for my grandparents as youngsters these days generally do not know these old-school traditional confectioneries.

As a Hokkien-lang, I still remember my grandmother giving me a slice (because itâ€™s really much bigger than the usual mooncakes) when I was young during Mid-Autumn Festival. This brings back lots of childhood memories, including old-school, heritage playgrounds such as the one shaped like a watermelon in Tampines. Traditions will be lost forever if we do not continue to preserve it and upkeep them.â€œ

Captured by @stormscape for #SingapoRediscovers. Comment below and share with us your childhood Mid-Autumn memories.

Find out more in our Instagram Stories.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct]Â  Ancient South Indian Temple architectural with a respect for harmonious coexistence re-discovered

Rediscovery is about relooking and appreciate the coexistence of interesting elements in an environment

I learned about Sri Senpaga only recently and decided to re-discover this amazing temple built with ancient South Indian temple architectural style that flourished in the 7th-century Chola dynasty. This temple was established in the 1850s by Ceylonese Tamils from Sri Lanka which explains the differencesÂ  from the usual Hindu temple that I have seen.

 Two things captured my attention. Firstly, it is the Â 21-metre tall, five-tiered structure at the main entrance that looks amazing with the glow from the morning sun. The intrigued details are very impressive.Â 
Secondly, it was the signage that says â€œAll are welcomeâ€. You need to read the signage in detail to be impressed by how welcoming they are regardless of different race and religion. That signage as well as the temple represents what is unique about Singapore - Our harmoniousÂ  coexistence of different races and religions into what is Singapore.

Hope to visit this temple more
